ng at the 2009 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 800 metre freestyle|800 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | [[Swimming at the 2003 World Aquatics Championships|2003 Barcelona]] | [[Swimming at the 2003 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 400 metre individual medley|400 m  medley]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | [[Swimming at the 2005 World Aquatics Championships|2005 Montreal]] | [[Swimming at the 2005 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 400 metre freestyle|400 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | 2005 Montreal | [[Swimming at the 2005 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 400 metre individual medley|400 m medley]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | 2013 Barcelona | [[Open water swimming at the 2013 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 10 km|10 km open water]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|World Championships (SC)]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2004 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2004 Indianapolis]] | 400 m medley}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2010 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2010 Dubai]] | [[2010 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 1500 metre freestyle|1500 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | 2010 Dubai | [[2010 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 400 metre individual medley|400 m medley]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2014 Doha]] | [[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 1500 metre freestyle|1500 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | {{nowrap|2004 Indianapolis}} | 200 m medley}}\n{{MedalBronze | 2010 Dubai | [[2010 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 200 metre freestyle|200 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | 2010 Dubai | [[2010 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Men's 400 metre freestyle|400 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Swimming at the Mediterranean Games|Mediterranean Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2005 Mediterranean Games|2005 Almer\u00eda]] | 800 m freestyle}}\n{{MedalGold | 2005 Almer\u00eda | 200 m medley}}\n{{MedalGold | 2005 Almer\u00eda | 400 m medley}}\n{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2009 Mediterranean Games|2009 Pescara]] | 200 m freestyle}}\n{{MedalGold | 2009 Pescara | 200 m medley}}\n{{MedalGold | 2009 Pescara | 400 m freestyle}}\n{{MedalGold | 2009 Pescara | 400 m medley}}\n{{MedalGold | 2009 Pescara | 1500 m freestyle}}\n{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2013 Mediterranean Games|2013 Mersin]] | 400 m medley}}\n{{MedalGold | 2013 Mersin | 1500 m freestyle}}\n{{MedalSilver | [[Swimming at the 2001 Mediterranean Games|2001 Tunis]] | 400 m medley}}\n{{MedalSilver | 2013 Mersin | 200 m freestyle}}\n{{MedalSilver | 2013 Mersin | 200 m medley}}\n{{MedalSilver | 2013 Mersin | 400 m freestyle}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Pan Arab Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2011 Pan Arab Games|2011 Doha]] | 50 m freestyle}}\n{{MedalGold | 2011 Doha | 100 m freestyle}}\n{{MedalGold | 2011 Doha | 200 m freestyle}}\n{{MedalGold | 2011 Doha | 400 m freestyle}}\n{{MedalGold | 2011 Doha | 1500 m freestyle}}\n{{MedalGold | 2011 Doha | 100 m backstroke}}\n{{MedalGold | 2011 Doha | 200 m backstroke}}\n{{MedalGold | 2011 Doha | {{nowrap|200 m breaststroke}}}}\n{{MedalGold | 2011 Doha | 50 m butterfly}}\n{{MedalGold | 2011 Doha | 100 m butterfly}}\n{{MedalGold | 2011 Doha | 200 m butterfly}}\n{{MedalGold | 2011 Doha | 200 m medley}}\n{{MedalGold | 2011 Doha | 400 m medley}}\n{{MedalGold | 2011 Doha | 4\u00d7100 m freestyle}}\n{{MedalGold | 2011 Doha | 4\u00d7200 m freestyle}}\n{{MedalSilver | 2011 Doha| 4\u00d7100 m medley}}\n}}\n\n'''Oussama \"Ous\" Mellouli''' ({{lang-ar|'''\u0623\u0633\u0627\u0645\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u0648\u0644\u064a'''}}; born 16 February 1984) is a Tunisian [[swimmer]] who competes in the [[freestyle swimming|freestyle]] and [[medley swimming|medley]] events. He is a three-time Olympic medalist, is an [[African records in swimming|African record]] holder, and trains with the USC Trojans team based at the [[University of Southern California]], where he studied as a computer science undergraduate and swam collegiately.\n\nSince returning from an Adderall related drugs ban, Oussama Mellouli has been the 1500 m freestyle World champion at the [[2009 World Aquatics Championships]] with a winning time of 14:37.28, then the second best performance of all time. Mellouli was the gold medalist in the [[Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 1500 metre freestyle|1500 freestyle]] at the 2008 Olympics, the bronze medalist in the 1500 freestyle at the [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 Olympics]], and the gold medalist in the 10&nbsp;km marathon swim at the 2012 Olympics. He is the first Olympian to win medals in both the open water and the pool in a single Olympics<ref>https://swimswam.com/ous-mellouli-looking-repeat-gold-rio/</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Tunis]], Mellouli left Tunisia at the age of 15 to study and train in [[France]]. He enrolled in [[University of Southern California|USC]] [[USC Viterbi School of Engineering|Viterbi School of Engineering]] in 2003 after graduating from the Lycee Technologique du Rempart in [[Marseille]], France. He swam for the USC Trojans and graduated in 2007 with a computer science bachelor's degree. He is a scholarship holder with the [[Olympic Solidarity]] program.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n==Swimming Timeline==\n===2001===\nMellouli won 1 silver medal in the 400m IM at the [[2001 Mediterranean Games]], in [[Tunis]], [[Tunisia]].\n\n===2003===\nMellouli first established himself on the world scene at the [[2003 World Aquatics Championships|2003 World Championships]] in [[Barcelona|Barcelona, Spain]] where he won a bronze in the 400m Individual Medley finishing behind [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Cseh]] and a world record performance from [[Michael Phelps]].\n\n===2004===\nAt the [[2004 Summer Olympics|2004 Olympics]] he finished 5th in the 400 IM, setting the [[African records in swimming|African Record]] in the process. He further distinguished himself at the [[2004 FINA Short Course World Championships]] in [[Indianapolis, Indiana|Indianapolis, USA]] where he won the first international-level gold medal in swimming for [[Tunisia]], in the 400m IM, finishing over a second ahead of second and third-place finishers [[Robin Francis]] and [[Eric Shanteau]]. Later on at the meet he would go on to win bronze in the 200m IM.\n\n===2005===\nHe was able to better his Athens mark with his bronze-medal swim in the 400 IM event at the [[2005 World Aquatics Championships]] in [[Montreal|Montreal, Canada]].  He also won the bronze-medal in the 400 freestyle at that same event. He also won three gold medals (800 m freestyle, 400m medley, 200m medley) at the [http://www.almeria2005.es XVth Mediterranean Games] in Almer\u00eda, Spain.\n\n===2006===\nOn 1 December 2006 Elias beat Michael Phelps in the 400m IM at the U.S. Open in West Lafayette: Mellouli clocked 4:15.61, ahead of Phelps with 4:18.32.<ref>[http://www.usaswimming.org/USASWeb/_Rainbow/Documents/601b51f2-d2a0-46fb-aef3-e1e9772b519b/061130F020.htm US Open 2006 results: Men's 400 IM final]. Archived on the [[USA Swimming]] website and retrieved 2009-07-23.</ref> This swim however was subsequently placed within Mellouli's 18-month doping ban, and the results nullified, as the drug test where the banned substance was found occurred at this meet (see section below for further information).\n\n===2007===\nOn 19 February 2007 he broke his own African Record in the 200m individual medley for the fourth time since 2003 at the [[USA Swimming]] Grand Prix meet, held at the [[Mizzou Aquatic Center]] at the [[University of Missouri]]. He also set a new African record in the 400 meter individual medley.\n\nOn 25 March 2007 he won the silver in the [[Swimming at the 2007 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 400 metre freestyle|400 m freestyle]] (3:45.12) at the [[2007 World Aquatics Championships|2007 World Championships]] in Melbourne, Australia. Three days later, on 28 March, he swam to the first Tunisian World Championship in swimming in winning the [[Swimming at the 2007 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 800 metre freestyle|800m freestyle]] in a then [[List of African records in swimming|African Record]] of 7:46.95 \u2014 one of the top 10 fastest times ever. However, due to his positive drug-testing result from a in-competition test from December 2006 and the 18-month competition ban imposed on him on 11 September 2007 by the [[Court of Arbitration for Sport]] (CAS), retroactive from 30 November 2006 forward, his 2007 World Championships results have been nullified. He was also a finalist in the [[Swimming at the 2007 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 400 metre individual medley|400 m individual medley]], where he originally finished fourth in 4:11.68.\n\nFollowing the 11 September 2007 ruling by CAS, Mellouli was not allowed to compete again up mid-2008. All of Mellouli's results from 2007 have been nullified, per his September 2007 doping suspension, related to his positive test from December 2006 (see section below).\n\n===2008 Olympics===\nMellouli came into the [[Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Olympics]] in Beijing, China entered in two events, the 400m and 1500m freestyle events. In his first event, the 400m free despite setting a new African record in the final, he could only manage fifth place in a time of 3:43.45. Mellouli would however go on to win the [[Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 1500 metre freestyle|1500m freestyle]] and set a new African record. In doing so, he became the first African male swimmer to ever win an Olympic gold medal in an individual swimming event (the South African men's 4 \u00d7 100 m Free Relay won the event at the [[Swimming at the 2004 Summer Olympics|2004 Olympics]]).\n\n===2009===\nMellouli won 5 gold medals (200m and 400m individual medley, and 200m, 400m and 1500m freestyles) at the [[Swimming at the 2009 Mediterranean Games|XVI Mediterranean Games]] in Pescara, Italy.\n\nIn the [[2009 World Aquatics Championships]], held in Rome during the summer, Mellouli won a gold medal in the 1500 meter freestyle and 2 silver medals in the 400 meter freestyle and 800 meter freestyle.\n\n===2010===\nMellouli won 4 medals ( 1 gold in the 1500 freestyle; 1 silver in the 400 medley and 2 bronzes in the 200 m freestyle and the 400 m freestyle) at the  [[2010 FINA Short Course World Championships]] (25m) in Dubai, UAE.\n\n===2011===\nMellouli won 16 medals ( 15 gold and 1 silver ) at the [[2011 Pan Arab Games]] in Doha, Qatar.\n\n===2012===\nMellouli won 2 medals (1 gold in the [[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's marathon 10 kilometre|10km marathon]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/london-olympics-2012/news/Mellouli-wins-mens-10km-swimming-marathon/articleshow/15436220.cms|title=Mellouli wins men's 10km swimming marathon|accessdate=10 August 2012}}</ref> and 1 bronze in the [[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 1500 metre freestyle|1500m freestyle]]) at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] held in London, UK. He became the first person to win medals in both pool and open-water swimming in the same Olympics.\n\n===2013===\nMellouli won 1 gold medal in the [[Open water swimming at the 2013 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 5 km|5km marathon]] at the [[2013 World Aquatics Championships|2013 World Championships]], in [[Barcelona|Barcelona, Spain]].\n\n===2016===\nMellouli participated in two competitions in [[Rio 2016 Summer Olympics]] but did not win any medals. In the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics - Men's 1500 metre freestyle|1500m freestyle]] he came first in his heat with 15:07.78 (considerably slower than his [[London 2012 Summer Olympics]] time of 14:40.31<ref>[https://www.olympic.org/oussama-mellouli Oussama MELLOULI - Olympic Swimming | Tunisia], olympic.org. Accessed August 23, 2016.</ref>) but ranked 21st in the competition thus did not qualify for the final. He also competed in the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics - Men's marathon 10 kilometre|10km marathon]] finishing in the 12th place with 1:53:06 (+0:00:07 of the gold winner).<ref>https://www.rio2016.com/en/athlete/oussama-mellouli</ref>.\n\n==Positive drug test==\nA few weeks after the conclusion of the [[2007 World Aquatics Championships|2007 World Championships]], reports began to surface that Mellouli had tested positive for a banned substance at the 2006 U.S. Open, 30 November \u2013 2 December 2006. These reports surfaced because [[FINA]], the international governing body of the sport, had discovered that Tunisian authorities had known about the positive test but had only given him a warning. FINA/WADA rules state that when an athlete tests positive for a banned substance, he or she must be given a 2-year ban from the sport.  Accordingly, FINA took the case to the [[Court of Arbitration for Sport]] (CAS), demanding stiffer sanction.\n\nMellouli has since admitted that he took the [[Attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder|ADD]] medication [[Adderall]], a [[stimulant]] and a form of [[amphetamine]]. (Already in June 2006, an American sports commentator wrote: ''Various studies show rampant use of Adderall, Ritalin and other drugs normally used for attention deficit disorder instead applied toward all-night cramming sessions.''<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060615032317/http://msnbc.msn.com/id/13214435/ \"Consider ending drug policies in sports: Maybe best solution is just to let pro athletes take whatever they want\"], Commentary by Bob Cook, ''[[MSNBC.com]]'', 10 June 2006. Retrieved on 2007-09-13.</ref> ) Mellouli did not have a prescription for the drug, having claimed to have received it from another [[University of Southern California|USC]] student shortly before the US Open. He argued that he took the pill in order to help himself with writing a [[term paper]] (to sustain or enhance his academic performance) in the days leading up to the weekend US Open meet, and that the drug was not intended as a performance-enhancing substance for competitive swimming. However, amphetamines are on the official banned substances list; and can/do help swimming performance.<ref>List of Drugs Prohibited by the WADA for years [http://www.wada-ama.org/rtecontent/document/list_2005.pdf 2005] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926025439/http://www.wada-ama.org/rtecontent/document/list_2005.pdf |date=2007-09-26 }} and [http://www.wada-ama.org/rtecontent/document/2006_LIST.pdf 2006] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080819211130/http://www.wada-ama.org/rtecontent/document/2006_LIST.pdf |date=2008-08-19 }} ([[portable document format|PDF]]) \u2013 relevant quote: ''The following stimulants are prohibited, including both their optical (D- and L-) isomers where relevant: ...amphetamine... and other substances with similar chemical structure or similar biological effect(s).'' (p. 7) This passage verbatim matches the content of article section [[Adderall#Chemistry]].</ref>\n\n{{Wikinews|Tunisian swimmer Oussama Mellouli stripped of championship for doping}}\nCAS ruled on Mellouli's case on 11 September 2007, ruling against him and issuing him an 18-month competition suspension, retroactively beginning on 30 November 2006. As a result of this sanction, all his results from the 2006 U.S. Open through the competitions his swam in 2007, including the 2007 World Championships, were nullified. His ban from competition covered most, but not all, of the qualification window for the 2008 Olympics. As the retroactive nullification of results wiped out all of his qualifying times for the 2008 Games, he ended up with just a week or two after the ban in order to qualify (which he did).\n\n==Achievements==\n* [[2013 World Aquatics Championships|2013 World Championships]] \u2013 1 gold medal ([[Open water swimming at the 2013 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 5 km|5 km marathon]]) and 1 bronze medal ([[Open water swimming at the 2013 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 10 km|10 k marathon]])\n* [[2012 Summer Olympics]] \u2013 gold medal ([[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's marathon 10 kilometre|10 km marathon]]) and bronze medal ([[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 1500 metre freestyle|1500 m freestyle]]).\n* [[2009 World Aquatics Championships|2009 World Championships]] \u2013 1 gold medal (1500 m freestyle) and 2 silver medals (400 m freestyle, 800 m freestyle)\n* [[2008 Summer Olympics]] \u2013 gold medal (1500 m freestyle)\n* [[2007 World Aquatics Championships|2007 World Championships]] \u2014 ''results nullified''.\n* [[2005 World Aquatics Championships|2005 World Championships]] \u2013 bronze medal (400m individual medley and 400m freestyle)\n* [[Swimming at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 400 metre individual medley|2004 Olympic Games]] \u2013 fifth place (400 m individual medley)\n* [[2004 FINA Short Course World Championships]] \u2013 bronze medal (200 m individual medley)\n* [[2004 FINA Short Course World Championships]] \u2013 gold medal (400 m individual medley)\n* [[2003 World Aquatics Championships|2003 World Championships]] \u2013 bronze medal (400 m individual medley)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Adderall#Performance-enhancing use]]\n* [[List of sportspeople sanctioned for doping offences]]\n* [[Tunisia at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Oussama Mellouli}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070425005120/http://www-scf.usc.edu/~oman/ITP104/OusWebsite/HomePage.htm Personal webpage of Oussama Mellouli at the University of Southern California]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{succession box|title=[[List of Swimming World Swimmers of the Year#African Swimmers of the Year|African Swimmer of the Year]]|before={{flagicon|RSA}} [[Roland Schoeman]]|after={{flagicon|RSA}} [[Cameron van der Burgh]]|years=2008,<br>2009 <small>(with {{flagicon|RSA}} Cameron van d