ing Commission]]|years=24 January 1966 \u2013 24 March 1977}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[M. C. Chagla|Mahommedali Currim Chagla]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of External Affairs (India)|Union Minister of External Affairs]]|years=6 September 1967 \u2013 13 February 1969}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Dinesh Singh (Uttar Pradesh politician)|Dinesh Singh]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Morarji Desai]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Finance (India)|Union Minister of Finance]]|years=16 January 1969 \u2013 15 March 1971}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Yashwantrao Chavan]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Home Affairs (India)|Union Minister of Home Affairs]]|years=27 June 1970 \u2013 4 February 1973}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Swaran Singh]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Defence (India)|Union Minister of Defence]]|years=1 December 1975 \u2013 25 December 1975}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bansi Lal]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Charan Singh]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of India]]|years=14 January 1980 \u2013 31 October 1984}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Rajiv Gandhi]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[Planning Commission (India)|Planning Commission]]|years=14 January 1980 \u2013 31 October 1984}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Chidambaram Subramaniam]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Defence (India)|Union Minister of Defence]]|years=16 January 1980 \u2013 15 January 1982}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[R. Venkataraman|Ramaswamy Venkataraman]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[P. V. Narasimha Rao|Narasimha Rao]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of External Affairs (India)|Union Minister of External Affairs]]|years=19 July 1984 \u2013 31 October 1984}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Rajiv Gandhi]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n}} \n{{Prime Ministers of India}}\n{{Bharat Ratna}}\n{{Indian National Congress Presidents}}\n{{Ministers of Information and Broadcasting}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gandhi, Indira}}\n[[Category:Indira Gandhi|*]]\n[[Category:1917 births]]\n[[Category:1984 deaths]]\n[[Category:4th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women]]\n[[Category:20th-century women rulers]]\n[[Category:Assassinated heads of government]]\n[[Category:Assassinated Indian politicians]]\n[[Category:Bandung Conference attendees]]\n[[Category:Children of Prime Ministers of India]]\n[[Category:People from Raebareli]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in India]]\n[[Category:Defence Ministers of India]]\n[[Category:Female defence ministers]]\n[[Category:Female foreign ministers]]\n[[Category:Finance Ministers of India]]\n[[Category:Indian Hindus]]\n[[Category:People associated with Santiniketan]]\n[[Category:Indian socialists]]\n[[Category:Kashmiri people]]\n[[Category:Lenin Peace Prize recipients]]\n[[Category:Ministers for External Affairs of India]]\n[[Category:Ministers for Information and Broadcasting of India]]\n[[Category:Ministers of Internal Affairs of India]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Nehru\u2013Gandhi family]]\n[[Category:People educated at Badminton School]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Delhi]]\n[[Category:People of the Emergency (India)]]\n[[Category:People who died in office]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Indian National Congress]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of India]]\n[[Category:Rajya Sabha members from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Bharat Ratna]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Cabinet of India]]\n[[Category:Women leaders of India]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Lok Sabha]]\n[[Category:Women prime ministers]]\n[[Category:Victims of Sikh terrorism]]\n[[Category:Assassination of Indira Gandhi]]\n[[Category:5th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:6th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:7th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:State funerals in India]]\n[[Category:Heads of regimes who were later imprisoned]]\n", "name_user": "Twofingered Typist", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSouth Asia:rem duplicate WP links; added WP links; wording; edits for flow; punctuation; fixed wording->Indian English", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indira_Gandhi"}
{"title_page": "Gender bias on Wikipedia", "text_new": "{{short description|Gender gap problem in Wikipedia and Wikimedia projects}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n'''Gender bias on Wikipedia''' reflects findings that a dominant majority of volunteer Wikipedia editors, particularly on the [[English Wikipedia|English-language site]], are male. Also, there are fewer and less extensive articles about women or topics important to women.\nIt figures among the most frequent [[criticism of Wikipedia|criticisms of Wikipedia]], sometimes as part of a more general criticism about [[systemic bias in Wikipedia]]. The [[Wikimedia Foundation]], which runs Wikipedia, agrees with these criticisms and has made an ongoing attempt to increase female editorship of Wikipedia. [[Edit-a-thon]]s have been held to encourage female editors and increase the coverage of women's topics.<ref name=tnw>{{cite web|url=https://thenextweb.com/tech/2019/03/19/physicist-has-written-over-500-biographies-female-scientists-wikipedia/|website=thenextweb.com|first=Cara|last=Curtis|year=2019|title=This physicist has written over 500 biographies of women scientists on Wikipedia|publisher=[[The Next Web]]|access-date=10 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804235220/https://thenextweb.com/tech/2019/03/19/physicist-has-written-over-500-biographies-female-scientists-wikipedia/|archive-date=4 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=indy500>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/science-women-wikipedia-biography-sexism-academia-physics-a-level-a8773631.html|title=This is why I've written 500 biographies of female scientists on Wikipedia|first=Jessica|last=Wade|date=11 February 2019|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|authorlink=Jess Wade|accessdate=25 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190520230025/https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/science-women-wikipedia-biography-sexism-academia-physics-a-level-a8773631.html|archive-date=20 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Research findings and issues==\nA 2015 survey of contributors to Wikipedia found that less than  15%  of  contributors  were  women. This gender contribution has received significant attention from researchers and the media. A group of researchers and practitioners offered several opinions on why this has been an issue. The gender research literature  suggests that  the  difference  in  contribution  rates  could  be  due  to three factors:  (1) the high levels of conflict in discussions, (2)  dislike  of  critical  environments,  and  (3)  lack  of confidence in editing other contributors' work.<ref>https://dl.acm.org/doi/pdf/10.1145/2145204.2145265</ref><ref name=nytimes20jun2015>{{cite web |author1 = Andrew Lih |title = Can Wikipedia Survive? |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/21/opinion/can-wikipedia-survive.html |website = www.nytimes.com |accessdate = 21 June 2015 |location = Washington |date = 20 June 2015 |quote = ...the considerable and often-noted gender gap among Wikipedia editors; in 2011, less than 15 percent were women. |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150621032208/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/21/opinion/can-wikipedia-survive.html |archivedate = 21 June 2015 |df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=EditorSurveys>Statistics based on Wikimedia Foundation Wikipedia editor surveys [https://wikimediafoundation.org/w/index.php?title=File%3AEditor_Survey_Report_-_April_2011.pdf&page=1 2011] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170702163818/https://wikimediafoundation.org/w/index.php?title=File%3AEditor_Survey_Report_-_April_2011.pdf&page=1 |date=2 July 2017 }} (Nov. 2010-April 2011) and [http://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Research:Wikipedia_Editors_Survey_November_2011 November 2011] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605124632/https://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Research:Wikipedia_Editors_Survey_November_2011 |date=5 June 2016 }} (April \u2013 October 2011)</ref><ref name=PLOS>{{cite journal |last1 = Hill |first1 = Benjamin Mako |last2 = Shaw |first2 = Aaron |last3 = S\u00e1nchez |first3 = Angel |title = The Wikipedia Gender Gap Revisited: Characterizing Survey Response Bias with Propensity Score Estimation |journal = PLoS ONE |date = 26 June 2013 |volume = 8 |issue = 6 |pages = e65782 |doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0065782 |pmid = 23840366 |pmc = 3694126 |bibcode = 2013PLoSO...865782H |df = dmy-all }}</ref> Consequently, Wikipedia has been criticized by some academics and journalists for having primarily male contributors,<ref name=Cohen110130 /><ref>{{cite web |url = http://firstmonday.org/article/view/4291/3381 |title = \"Free as in sexist?\": Free culture and the gender gap |work = [[First Monday (journal)|First Monday]] |accessdate = 10 October 2015 |author = Reagle, Joseph |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150520205049/http://firstmonday.org/article/view/4291/3381 |archivedate = 20 May 2015 |df = dmy-all |author-link = Joseph Reagle }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://surprisinglyfree.com/2013/02/26/joseph-reagle-2/ |title = Joseph Reagle on the gender gap in geek culture |date = 26 February 2013 |accessdate = 10 October 2015 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151117015917/http://surprisinglyfree.com/2013/02/26/joseph-reagle-2/ |archivedate = 17 November 2015 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> and for having fewer and less extensive articles about women or topics important to women. ''[[The New York Times]]'' pointed out that Wikipedia's female participation rate may be in line with other \"public thought-leadership forums\".<ref name=Cohen110130 /> In 2009, a Wikimedia Foundation survey revealed that 6% of editors who made more than 500 edits were female, with the average male editor having twice as many edits.<ref name=Clubhouse>{{cite web |url = http://www-users.cs.umn.edu/~lam/papers/wp-gender-wikisym2011.pdf |title = WP:Clubhouse? An Exploration of Wikipedia's Gender Imbalance |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150418072510/http://www-users.cs.umn.edu/~lam/papers/wp-gender-wikisym2011.pdf |archivedate = 18 April 2015 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn the English Wikipedia and five other language editions that were studied by researchers, the ratio of articles about women to articles about men was higher than in three other databases. However, analysis with computational linguistics concluded that the way women and men are described in articles demonstrates bias, with articles about women more likely to use more words relating to gender and family. The researchers believe that this is a sign Wikipedia editors consider male the \"null gender\" (in other words, that \"male\" is assumed unless otherwise specified, an example of [[male as norm]]).<ref>{{Cite news |url = https://www.technologyreview.com/s/534616/computational-linguistics-reveals-how-wikipedia-articles-are-biased-against-women/ |title = Computational Linguistics Reveals How Wikipedia Articles Are Biased Against Women |last = arXiv |first = Emerging Technology from the |work = MIT Technology Review |access-date = 21 August 2017 |archive-url = https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20170927024309/https://www.technologyreview.com/s/534616/computational-linguistics-reveals-how-wikipedia-articles-are-biased-against-women/ |archive-date = 27 September 2017 |url-status = live }}</ref> Another critique of Wikipedia's approach, from a 2014 ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' editorial, is that it has difficulty making judgments about \"what matters\". To illustrate this point they noted that [[List of pornographic actresses by decade|the page listing pornographic actresses]] was better organized than [[List of women writers|the page listing women writers]].<ref name=GuardianAugust2014>''[[The Guardian]]'' 2014 (London) [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/aug/07/guardian-view-wikipedia-evolving-truth The Guardian view on Wikipedia: evolving truth] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112212758/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/aug/07/guardian-view-wikipedia-evolving-truth |date=12 November 2016 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none;\"\n|+ style=\"text-align: left; font-weight: normal; font-size: 80%\" | Comparison of results for the proportion of Wikipedia readers and editors from the nationally representative Pew survey and the WMF/UNU-MERIT survey (UNU) for a series of dichotomous variables in both surveys. Adjusted numbers for editors assume that response bias for editors is identical to observed response bias for readers and, in the rightmost column, that bias is stable for editors outside the United States. Table reproduced from <ref name=\"PLOS\" />.\n! Variable\n! Readers US (Pew)\n! Readers US (UNU)\n! Editors US (UNU)\n! Editors US Adj.\n! Editors (UNU)\n! Editors Adj.\n|-\n| female\n| 49.0\n| 39.9\n| 17.8\n| 22.7\n| 12.7\n| 16.1\n|-\n| married\n| 60.1\n| 44.1\n| 30.9\n| 36.3\n| 33.2\n| 38.4\n|-\n| children\n| 36.0\n| 29.4\n| 16.4\n| 27.6\n| 14.4\n| 25.3\n|-\n| immigrant\n| 10.1\n| 14.4\n| 12.1\n| 9.8\n| 8.2\n| 7.4\n|-\n| student\n| 17.7\n| 29.9\n| 46.0\n| 38.5\n| 47.7\n| 40.3\n|}\n\nIn 2010, [[United Nations University]] and [[UNU-MERIT]] jointly presented an overview of the results of a global Wikipedia survey.<ref name=WPSurvey2010>{{cite web |title = Wikipedia Survey: Overview Results |url = http://www.wikipediasurvey.org/docs/Wikipedia_Overview_15March2010-FINAL.pdf |last1 = Glott |first1 = Ruediger |last2 = Schmidt |first2 = Philipp |last3 = Ghosh |first3 = Rishab |date = March 2010 |website =  |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100414165445/http://wikipediasurvey.org/docs/Wikipedia_Overview_15March2010-FINAL.pdf |archivedate = 14 April 2010 |accessdate = 11 August 2014 }}</ref> A 30 January 2011, ''New York Times'' article cited this [[Wikimedia Foundation]] collaboration, which indicated that fewer than 13% of contributors to Wikipedia are women.  [[Sue Gardner]], then executive director of the foundation, said that increasing diversity was about making the encyclopedia \"as good as it could be\". Factors the article cited as possibly discouraging women from editing included the \"obsessive fact-loving realm\", associations with the \"hard-driving hacker crowd\", and the necessity to be \"open to very difficult, high-conflict people, even misogynists\".<ref name=Cohen110130>{{cite news |last = Cohen |first = Noam |date = 30 January 2011 |title = Define Gender Gap? Look Up Wikipedia's Contributor List |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/31/business/media/31link.html |newspaper = New York Times |accessdate = 31 January 2011 |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110203043906/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/31/business/media/31link.html |archivedate = 3 February 2011 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> In 2013, the results of the survey were challenged by Hill and Shaw using corrective estimation techniques to suggest upward corrections to the data from the survey and to recommend updates to the statistics being surveyed, giving 22.7% for adult US female editors and 16.1% overall.<ref name=PLOS />\n\nIn February 2011, ''The New York Times'' followed up with a series of opinions on the subject under the banner, \"Where Are the Women in Wikipedia?\"<ref name=WhereAretheWomen>{{cite news |author = <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date = 2 February 2011 |title = Where Are the Women in Wikipedia? |url = https://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2011/02/02/where-are-the-women-in-wikipedia |newspaper = New York Times |accessdate = 9 August 2014 |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140715112226/http://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2011/02/02/where-are-the-women-in-wikipedia |archivedate = 15 July 2014 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> [[Susan Herring|Susan C. Herring]], a professor of information science and linguistics, said that she was not surprised by the Wikipedia contributors' gender gap. She said that the often contentious nature of Wikipedia article \"talk\" pages, where article content is discussed, is unappealing to many women, \"if not outright intimidating\".<ref name=Herring110204>{{cite news |last = Herring |first = Susan C. |date = 4 February 2011 |title = Communication Styles Make a Difference |url = https://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2011/02/02/where-are-the-women-in-wikipedia/communication-styles-make-a-difference |type = opinion |newspaper = New York Times |accessdate = 11 August 2014 |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140724050237/http://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2011/02/02/where-are-the-women-in-wikipedia/communication-styles-make-a-difference |archivedate = 24 July 2014 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> [[Joseph Reagle|Joseph M. Reagle]] reacted similarly, saying that the combination of a \"culture of hacker elitism\", combined with the disproportionate effect of high-conflict members (a minority) on the community atmosphere, can make it unappealing. He said, \"the ideology and rhetoric of freedom and openness can then be used (a) to suppress concerns about inappropriate or offensive speech as \"censorship\" and (b) to rationalize low female participation as simply a matter of their personal preference and choice.\"<ref name=Reagle110204>{{cite news |last = Reagle |first = Joseph M. |date = 4 February 2011 |title = 'Open' Doesn't Include Everyone |url = https://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2011/02/02/where-are-the-women-in-wikipedia/open-doesnt-include-everyone |type = opinion |newspaper = New York Times |accessdate = 11 August 2014 |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140715113229/http://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2011/02/02/where-are-the-women-in-wikipedia/open-doesnt-include-everyone |archivedate = 15 July 2014 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> [[Justine Cassell]] said that although women are as knowledgeable as men, and as able to defend their point of view, \"it is still the case in American society that debate, contention, and vigorous defense of one\u2019s position is often still seen as a male stance, and women\u2019s use of these speech styles can call forth negative evaluations.\"<ref name=Cassell110204>{{cite news |last = Cassell |first = Justine |date = 4 February 2011 |title = Editing Wars Behind the Scenes |url = https://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2011/02/02/where-are-the-women-in-wikipedia/a-culture-of-editing-wars |type = opinion |newspaper = New York Times |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170227113525/http://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2011/02/02/where-are-the-women-in-wikipedia/a-culture-of-editing-wars |archivedate = 27 February 2017 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n{{external media |width=220px | float=right |header-image=[[File:WP BOLD.jpg|220px|link=|alt=]] |video1=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=of93QwXixJg Research proves gender imbalance on Wikipedia], 2:45, [[University of Minnesota]]<ref name=\"UofM\">{{cite web |title=University of Minnesota researchers reveal Wikipedia gender biases |publisher=[[University of Minnesota]] |url=https://cse.umn.edu/news-release/university-of-minnesota-researchers-reveal-wikipedia-gender-biases/ |access-date=21 November 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161208081140/https://cse.umn.edu/news-release/university-of-minnesota-researchers-reveal-wikipedia-gender-biases/ |archive-date=8 December 2016 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|video2=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VZisBB3N4gg Where Are All the Women? Wikipedia\u2019s Gender Gap], 1:12:40, [[West Virginia University]]<ref name=\"WVU\">{{cite web |title=Tackling Wikipedia's Gender Gap |publisher=[[West Virginia University]] |url=http://reedcollegeofmedia.wvu.edu/about/featured-events/wiki-panel |access-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307141703/http://reedcollegeofmedia.wvu.edu/about/featured-events/wiki-panel |archive-date=7 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n}}\nThe ''[[International Journal of Communication]]'' published research by Reagle and Lauren Rhue that examined the coverage, gender representation, and article length of thousands of biographical subjects on the English-language Wikipedia and the online ''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica''. They concluded that Wikipedia provided better coverage and longer articles in general, that Wikipedia typically has more articles on women than ''Britannica'' in absolute terms, but Wikipedia articles on women were more likely to be missing than articles on men relative to ''Britannica''. That is, Wikipedia dominated ''Britannica'' in biographical coverage, but more so when it comes to men. Similarly, one might say that ''Britannica'' is more balanced in whom it neglects to cover than Wikipedia. For both reference works, article length did not consistently differ by gender.<ref name=\"Reagle-Rhue\">{{cite journal |last1 = Reagle |first1 = Joseph |last2 = Rhue |first2 = Lauren |title = Gender Bias in Wikipedia and ''Britannica'' |url = http://ijoc.org/index.php/ijoc/article/viewFile/777/631 |year = 2011 |journal = International Journal of Communication |volume = 5 |publisher = Joseph Reagle & Lauren Rhue |pages = 1138\u20131158 |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160322081809/http://ijoc.org/index.php/ijoc/article/viewFile/777/631 |archivedate = 22 March 2016 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2011, the Wikimedia Foundation conducted its first semi-annual Wikipedia survey. It suggested that 9% of Wikipedia editors are women. It also reported, \"Contrary to the perception of some, our data shows that very few women editors feel like they have been harassed, and very few feel Wikipedia is a sexualized environment.\"<ref name=WES2011>{{cite web |url = https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/76/Editor_Survey_Report_-_April_2011.pdf |title = Wikipedia Editors Study: Results From ''The Editor Survey, April 2011'' |date = April 2011 |website = [[Wikipedia]] |accessdate = 18 May 2014 |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141226041321/http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/76/Editor_Survey_Report_-_April_2011.pdf |archivedate = 26 December 2014 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> However, an October 2011 paper at the [[WikiSym|International Symposium on Wikis and Open Collaboration]] found evidence that suggested that Wikipedia may have \"a culture that may be resistant to female participation\".<ref name=WPClubhouse>{{cite conference |last1 = Lam |first1 = Shyong K. |last2 = Uduwage |first2 = Anuradha |last3 = Dong |first3 = Zhenhua |last4 = Sen |first4 = Shilad |last5 = Musicant |first5 = David R. |last6 = Terveen |first6 = Loren |last7 = Reidl |first7 = John |date = October 2011 |title = WP:Clubhouse? An Exploration of Wikipedia's Gender Imbalance |url = http://files.grouplens.org/papers/wp-gender-wikisym2011.pdf |conference = WikiSym'11 |conference-url = http://www.wikisym.org/ws2011/ |publisher = ACM |authorlink6 = Loren Terveen |authorlink7 = John T. Riedl |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131029232437/http://files.grouplens.org/papers/wp-gender-wikisym2011.pdf |archivedate = 29 October 2013 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nA study published in 2014 found that there is also an \"Internet skills gap\" with regard to Wikipedia editors. The authors found that the most likely Wikipedia contributors are high-skilled men and that there is no gender gap among low-skilled editors, and concluded that the \"skills gap\" exacerbates the gender gap among editors.<ref>{{cite journal |last1 = Hargittai |first1 = Eszter |last2 = Shaw |first2 = Aaron |title = Mind the skills gap: the role of Internet know-how and gender in differentiated contributions to Wikipedia |journal = Information, Communication & Society |date = 4 November 2014 |pages = 424\u2013442 |doi = 10.1080/1369118X.2014.957711 |volume = 18 |issue = 4 }}</ref> During 2010\u201314, women made up 61% of participants of the college courses arranged by the Wiki Education Foundation program that included editing Wikipedia as part of the curriculum. Their contributions were found to shift the Wikipedia content from pop-culture and [[Science, technology, engineering, and mathematics|STEM]] towards social sciences and humanities.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.sacbee.com/2014/09/23/6727564/bruce-maiman-wikipedia-grows-up.html |title = Wikipedia grows up on college campuses |author = Bruce Maiman |date = 23 September 2014 |website = [[The Sacramento Bee]] |accessdate = 23 September 2014 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140923224639/http://www.sacbee.com/2014/09/23/6727564/bruce-maiman-wikipedia-grows-up.html |archivedate = 23 September 2014 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Wagner et al.<ref>{{cite journal |last1 = Wagner |first1 = Claudia |last2 = Graells-Garrido |first2 = Eduardo |last3 = Garcia |first3 = David |last4 = Menczer |first4 = Filippo |title = Women through the glass ceiling: gender asymmetries in Wikipedia |journal = EPJ Data Science |date = 1 March 2016 |doi = 10.1140/epjds/s13688-016-0066-4 |volume = 5 |number = 5|arxiv = 1601.04890 }}</ref> found that gender inequality manifests itself in Wikipedia's biographical content in multiple ways, including unequal thresholds for determining a subject's notability, topical bias, linguistic bias, and structural inequalities. The authors found that when editors determine if a subject is notable enough to include on Wikipedia, they hold women to a higher standard of notability, resulting in women on Wikipedia being slightly more notable than men on Wikipedia. As for topical bias, biographies about women tend to focus more on family-, gender-, and relationship-related topics. This is especially true for biographies of women born before 1900. The authors also found structural differences in terms of meta-data and hyperlinks, which have consequences for information-seeking activities.\n\nA 2017 study found that women participating in an experiment by editing a Wikipedia-like site tended to view other editors as male, and to view their responses as more critical than if the other editor was [[gender-neutral]]. The study concluded that:<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shane-Simpson |first1=Christina |last2=Gillespie-Lynch |first2=Kristen |title=Examining potential mechanisms underlying the Wikipedia gender gap through a collaborative editing task |journal=[[Computers in Human Behavior]] |date=January 2017 |volume=66 |pages=312\u2013328 |doi=10.1016/j.chb.2016.09.043 |url=https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-01612306/document |access-date=4 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181104170109/https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-01612306/document |archive-date=4 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{quote |text = ...visible female editors on Wikipedia and broader encouragement of the use of constructive feedback may begin to alleviate the Wikipedia gender gap. Furthermore, the relatively high proportion of anonymous editors may exacerbate the Wikipedia gender gap, as anonymity may often be perceived as male and more critical.}}\n\nA study by Ford and Wajcman observes that research on the gender bias continues to frame the problem as a deficit in women. In contrast, their central argument states that infrastructure studies in [[feminist technoscience]] allows the gender analysis to be taken to a further level. It looks at three issues within the infrastructure: content policies, software, and the legalistic framework of operation. It suggests that progress can be made through altering that culture of [[knowledge production]] through encouraging alternate knowledge, reducing the technical barriers to editing, and addressing the complexity of Wikipedia policies.<ref>{{cite journal |last1 = Ford |first1 = Heather |last2 = Wajcman |first2 = Judy |title = 'Anyone can edit', not everyone does: Wikipedia and the gender gap |journal = Social Studies of Science |date = 2017 |url = http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/68675/ |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20161228081909/http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/68675/ |archivedate = 28 December 2016 |df = dmy-all | doi = 10.1177/0306312717692172 |pmid = 28791929 |volume=47 |issue = 4 |pages=511\u2013527}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, in the Pipeline of Online Participation Inequalities, Shaw and Hargittai concluded from their studies that to solve the problems of participation inequality including gender bias requires a broader focus on subjects other than inequality.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite journal|last=Shaw|first=Aaron|last2=Hargittai|first2=Eszter|date=2018-02-01|title=The Pipeline of Online Participation Inequalities: The Case of Wikipedia Editing|journal=Journal of Communication|volume=68|issue=1|pages=143\u2013168|doi=10.1093/joc/jqx003|issn=0021-9916}}</ref> They recommended a focus on encouraging participants of all educational backgrounds, skill levels, and age groups will help Wikipedia to improve. They recommended further that informing more women that Wikipedia is free to edit and open to everyone is critical in eliminating gender bias.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nIn March 2018, mathematician [[Marie A. Vitulli]] wrote in ''[[Notices of the American Mathematical Society]]'', \"The percentage of women editors on Wikipedia remains dismally low.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.ams.org/journals/notices/201803/rnoti-p330.pdf|title=Writing Women in Mathematics into Wikipedia 65 (3). pp. 331\u2013332. doi:10.1090/noti1650|last=Vitulli|first=Marie A.|date=March 2018|publisher=Notices of the American Mathematical Society|access-date=11 October 2018|doi=10.1090/noti1650|journal=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303142204/http://www.ams.org/journals/notices/201803/rnoti-p330.pdf|archive-date=3 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, when [[Donna Strickland]] won a [[Nobel Prize in Physics]], numerous write-ups mentioned that she did not previously have a Wikipedia page. A draft had been submitted, but was rejected for not demonstrating \"significant coverage (not just passing mentions) about the subject\".<ref>{{cite web |title=The Nobel prize winning scientist who wasn't famous enough for Wikipedia |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/people/the-nobel-prize-winning-scientist-who-wasn-t-famous-enough-for-wikipedia-1.3650212 |website=[[The Irish Times]] |accessdate=3 October 2018 |date=3 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003152517/https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/people/the-nobel-prize-winning-scientist-who-wasn-t-famous-enough-for-wikipedia-1.3650212 |archive-date=3 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/live/2018/oct/02/nobel-prize-in-physics-2018-live|title=Nobel physics prize winners include first female laureate for 55 years \u2013 as it happened|first=Nicola|last=Davis|date=2 October 2018|accessdate=27 February 2019|work=The Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190226083859/https://www.theguardian.com/science/live/2018/oct/02/nobel-prize-in-physics-2018-live|archive-date=26 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Leyland Cecco|title=Female Nobel prize winner deemed not important enough for Wikipedia entry|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2018/oct/03/donna-strickland-nobel-physics-prize-wikipedia-denied|work=The Guardian|date=2018-10-03|access-date=2018-10-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003195646/https://www.theguardian.com/science/2018/oct/03/donna-strickland-nobel-physics-prize-wikipedia-denied|archive-date=3 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Noopur Raval, a PhD candidate at UC Irvine, wrote in The Encyclopedia Must Fail!- Notes on Queering Wikipedia, that \"making a platform open access does not automatically translate to equality of participation, ease of access, or cultural acceptance of the medium.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Noopur|first=Raval|title=The Encyclopedia Must Fail! \u2013 Notes on Queering Wikipedia|url=https://adanewmedia.org/2014/07/issue5-raval/|journal=Ada: A Journal of Gender, New Media, and Technology|issue=\"5\"|doi=10.7264/N37W69GC|issn=2325-0496|year=2014|access-date=14 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014030644/https://adanewmedia.org/2014/07/issue5-raval/|archive-date=14 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2017, researchers Matthew A. Vetter and Keon Mandell Pettiway explain that the white, cis-gendered male dominance amongst Wikipedia editors has led to the \"erasure of non-normative gender and sexual identities,\" in addition to cis-gendered females. The \"androcentric and heteronormative discourses\" of Wikipedia editing insufficiently allow \"marginalized gender and sexual identities to take part in language use and the construction of knowledge.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|url=https://tcjournal.org/vol7/hacking-hetero-normative-logics|title=Hacking Hetero/Normative Logics: Queer Feminist Media Praxis in Wikipedia |journal= Technoculture|last=Matthew|first=Vetter|last2=Pettiway|first2=Keon|date=20 November 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014030646/https://tcjournal.org/vol7/hacking-hetero-normative-logics|archive-date=14 October 2019|access-date=2019-10-14|volume=7}}</ref>\n\n== Possible causes ==\n[[File:Sue Gardner Feb 2013 portrait crop 2.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Sue Gardner street portrait|Former Wikimedia Foundation executive director [[Sue Gardner]] provided nine reasons, offered by female [[Wikipedia editors]], \"Why Women Don't Edit Wikipedia.\"<ref name=Gardner110219 />]]\n\nSeveral causes for this gender disparity have been suggested. A 2010 study revealed a Wikipedia female participation rate of 13 percent, observed to be close to the 15 percent overall female participation rate of other \"public thought-leadership forums\".<ref name=Cohen110130 /><ref name=\"Signpost-2013-07-31\">{{cite web |url = https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Wikipedia_Signpost/2013-07-31/Recent_research |title = Recent research&nbsp;\u2014 Napoleon, Michael Jackson and Srebrenica across cultures, 90% of Wikipedia better than Britannica, WikiSym preview |last = Yasseri |first = Taha |last2 = Liao |first2 = Han-Teng |last3 = Konieczny |first3 = Piotr |last4 = Morgan |first4 = Jonathan |last5 = Bayer |first5 = Tilman |date = 31 July 2013 |work = [[Wikipedia:Wikipedia Signpost|The Signpost]] |publisher = [[Wikipedia]] |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150617074727/https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Wikipedia_Signpost/2013-07-31/Recent_research |archivedate = 17 June 2015 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> Wikipedia research fellow Sarah Stierch acknowledged that it is \"fairly common\" for Wikipedia contributors to remain gender-anonymous.<ref name=\"DailyDotStierch\">{{cite web |url = http://www.dailydot.com/society/wikipedia-gender-gap-sarah-stierch/ |title = The women of Wikipedia: Closing the site's giant gender gap |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150703203120/http://www.dailydot.com/society/wikipedia-gender-gap-sarah-stierch/ |archivedate = 3 July 2015 |df = dmy-all |date = 24 January 2013 }}</ref> A perceived unwelcoming culture and tolerance of violent and abusive language are also reasons put forth for the gender gap.<ref name=\"CSM-misogyny\">{{cite journal |url = http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Security-Watch/Backchannels/2013/0801/In-UK-rising-chorus-of-outrage-over-online-misogyny |title = In UK, rising chorus of outrage over online misogyny |journal = Christian Science Monitor |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150704200524/http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Security-Watch/Backchannels/2013/0801/In-UK-rising-chorus-of-outrage-over-online-misogyny |archivedate = 4 July 2015 |df = dmy-all |date = August 2013 }}</ref> According to a 2013 study,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url = http://dub.washington.edu/djangosite/media/papers/morgan_cscw2013_final.pdf |title = Tea & Sympathy: Crafting Positive New User Experiences on Wikipedia |author = Jonathan T. Morgan |author2 = Siko Bouterse |author3 = Sarah Stierch |author4 = Heather Walls |publisher = Wikimedia Foundation |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141105195335/http://dub.washington.edu/djangosite/media/papers/morgan_cscw2013_final.pdf |archivedate = 5 November 2014 |df = dmy-all |access-date = 24 August 2014 }}</ref> another cause of the gender gap in Wikipedia is the failure to attract and retain female editors, resulting in a negative impact on Wikipedia's coverage. As well, Wikipedia \"...editors that publicly identify as women face harassment\" from other Wikipedia editors.<ref name=\"Montellaro\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2015/11/how-does-political-pedia-stay-apolitical/450948/ |title=How Does Political Wikipedia Stay Apolitical?: The seventh-most visited site is one of the first online listings for any elected official\u2014but how does a site that stakes its reputation on neutrality walk that line |last=Montellaro |first=Zach |date=18 November 2015 |website=theatlantic.com |publisher=[[The Atlantic]] |access-date =20 August 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821004146/https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2015/11/how-does-political-wikipedia-stay-apolitical/450948/ |archive-date=21 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFormer Wikimedia Foundation executive director [[Sue Gardner]] cited nine reasons why women don't edit Wikipedia, culled from comments by female [[Wikipedia community|Wikipedia editors]]:<ref name=Gardner110219>{{cite web |last = Gardner |first = Sue |date = 19 February 2011 |title = Nine Reasons Why Women Don't Edit Wikipedia, In Their Own Words |url = http://suegardner.org/2011/02/19/nine-reasons-why-women-dont-edit-wikipedia-in-their-own-words/ |type = blog |website = suegardner.org |accessdate =  |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150718103642/http://suegardner.org/2011/02/19/nine-reasons-why-women-dont-edit-wikipedia-in-their-own-words/ |archive-date = 18 July 2015 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n# A lack of [[user-friendliness]] in the [[User interface|editing interface]] \n# Not having enough [[free time]] \n# A lack of [[self-confidence]]  \n# [[Conflict avoidance|Aversion to conflict]] and an unwillingness to participate in lengthy [[Criticism of Wikipedia#Level of debate, edit wars and harassment|edit wars]]  \n# Belief that their contributions are too likely to be reverted or deleted  \n# Some find its overall atmosphere [[Misogyny|misogynistic]] \n# Wikipedia culture is sexual in ways they find off-putting\n# Being addressed as male is off-putting to women whose primary language has grammatical gender\n# Fewer opportunities than other sites for social relationships and a welcoming tone\n\nThough the proportion of female readership to male readership on Wikipedia is roughly equal (47%), females are less likely to convert themselves to editors (16%). Several studies suggest that there may be a formed culture in Wikipedia that discourages women from participating.<ref name=\"WPClubhouse3\">{{cite conference|last1=Lam|first1=Shyong K.|last2=Uduwage|first2=Anuradha|last3=Dong|first3=Zhenhua|last4=Sen|first4=Shilad|last5=Musicant|first5=David R.|last6=Terveen|first6=Loren|authorlink6=Loren Terveen|last7=Reidl|first7=John|authorlink7=John T. Riedl|date=October 2011|title=WP:Clubhouse? An Exploration of Wikipedia's Gender Imbalance|url=http://files.grouplens.org/papers/wp-gender-wikisym2011.pdf|url-status=live|conference=WikiSym'11|publisher=ACM|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029232437/http://files.grouplens.org/papers/wp-gender-wikisym2011.pdf|archivedate=29 October 2013|conference-url=http://www.wikisym.org/ws2011/|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\":04\">{{Cite journal|last=Collier|first=Benjamin|last2=Bear|first2=Julia|date=2012|title=Conflict, criticism, or confidence: an empirical examination of the gender gap in wikipedia contributions|url=http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?doid=2145204.2145265|journal=Proceedings of the ACM 2012 Conference on Computer Supported Cooperative Work - CSCW '12|location=Seattle, Washington, USA|publisher=ACM Press|pages=383|doi=10.1145/2145204.2145265|isbn=9781450310864|access-date=1 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325090443/https://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?doid=2145204.2145265|archive-date=25 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Lam ''et al''. link this culture due to a disparity in male-to-female centric topics represented and edited, the tendency for female users to be more active in the social and community aspects of Wikipedia, an increased likelihood that edits by new female editors are reverted, and/or that articles with high proportions of female editors are more contentious.<ref name=\"WPClubhouse3\" />\n\nCollier and Bear in 2012 summarized the reason for working barriers of women in Wikipedia in three words: conflict, criticism and confidence. Conflict means [[online harassment]], [[trolling]] and competition which women generally do not like; Criticism refers to women's unwillingness to edit someone else's work and to let their work be edited by someone else; Confidence shows that women are often not too confident about their own expertise and ability in editing and contributing to a certain work.<ref name=\":04\" /> Wikipedia's free to edit policy gives Internet users an open platform, while also unconsciously breeding a competitive and critical environment that limits women's incentives to participate.\n\nThrough examining the power infrastructure of Wikipedia, Ford and Wajcman pointed out another cause that may reinforce Wikipedia's gender bias. Editing on Wikipedia requires \"particular forms of [[Sociotechnical system|sociotechnical]] expertise and authority that constitute the knowledge or [[epistemological]] infrastructure of Wikipedia\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ford|first=Heather|last2=Wajcman|first2=Judy|date=August 2017|title='Anyone can edit', not everyone does: Wikipedia's infrastructure and the gender gap|journal=Social Studies of Science|volume=47|issue=4|pages=511\u2013527|doi=10.1177/0306312717692172|pmid=28791929|issn=0306-3127|url=http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/68675/1/Wajcman_Anyone%20can%20edit_Final_2017.pdf|access-date=8 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919063205/http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/68675/1/Wajcman_Anyone%20can%20edit_Final_2017.pdf|archive-date=19 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>  People who are equipped with this expertise and skill are considered more likely to reach positions with power in Wikipedia. These are proposed to be predominantly men.\n\nStudies have also considered the gender bias in Wikipedia from a historical perspective. Konieczny and Klein indicated that Wikipedia is just a part of our biased society which has a long history of [[gender inequality]].<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Konieczny|first=Piotr|last2=Klein|first2=Maximilian|date=December 2018|title=Gender gap through time and space: A journey through Wikipedia biographies via the Wikidata Human Gender Indicator|journal=New Media & Society|volume=20|issue=12|pages=4608\u20134633|doi=10.1177/1461444818779080|issn=1461-4448}}</ref> As Wikipedia records daily activities by individual editors, it serves as both \"a reflection of the world\" and \"a tool used to produce our world\".<ref name=\":12\" /> Even though gender bias is reducing slowly, it remains an existing problem.\n\n== Reactions ==\n\nThe [[Wikimedia Foundation]] has officially held, since at least 2011 when Gardner was executive director, that gender bias exists in the project. It has made some attempts to address it but Gardner has expressed frustration with the degree of success achieved. She has also noted that \"in the very limited leisure time women had, they tended to be more involved in social activities instead of editing Wikipedia. 'Women see technology more as a tool they use to accomplish tasks, rather than something fun in itself.{{'\"}}<ref name=Huang130811>{{cite news |last = Huang |first = Keira |date = 11 August 2013 |title = Wikipedia fails to bridge gender gap |url = http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/article/1295872/wikipedia-fails-bridge-gender-gap |newspaper = South China Morning Post |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160115195821/http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/article/1295872/wikipedia-fails-bridge-gender-gap |archivedate = 15 January 2016 |df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=Wikistorm2013>{{cite web |url = http://femtechnet.newschool.edu/wikistorming/ |title = Wikistorming |date = Fall 2013 |website = FemTechNet |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150717034630/http://femtechnet.newschool.edu/wikistorming/ |archivedate = 17 July 2015 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> In 2011, the Foundation set a target of having 25 percent of its contributors identifying as female by 2015.<ref name=Cohen110130 /> In August 2013, Gardner said, \"I didn't solve it. We didn't solve it. The Wikimedia Foundation didn't solve it. The solution won't come from the Wikimedia Foundation.\"<ref name=Huang130811 />\n\nWriting for ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' in 2011, [[Heather Mac Donald]] called Wikipedia's gender imbalance a \"non-problem in search of a misguided solution.\" Mac Donald asserted, \"The most straightforward explanation for the differing rates of participation in Wikipedia\u2014and the one that conforms to everyday experience\u2014is  that, on average, males and females have different interests and preferred ways of spending their free time.\"<ref>{{cite web |last = Mac Donald |first = Heather |url = http://www.slate.com/articles/double_x/doublex/2011/02/wikipedia_is_maledominated_that_doesnt_mean_its_sexist.html |title = Wikipedia Is Male-Dominated. That Doesn't Mean It's Sexist. |website = [[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |date = 9 February 2011 |accessdate = 7 January 2015 |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150107205929/http://www.slate.com/articles/double_x/doublex/2011/02/wikipedia_is_maledominated_that_doesnt_mean_its_sexist.html |archivedate = 7 January 2015 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, Wikipedia co-founder [[Jimmy Wales]] announced in a BBC interview the [[Wikimedia Foundation]]'s plans for \"doubling down\" on the gender content gap at Wikipedia. Wales said the Foundation would be open to more outreach and more software changes.<ref name=\"BBC\">[https://www.bbc.com/news/business-28701772 Wikipedia 'completely failed' to fix gender imbalance] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161229004148/http://www.bbc.com/news/business-28701772 |date=29 December 2016 }}, [[BBC]] interview with [[Jimmy Wales]], 8 August 2014; starting at 45 seconds.</ref>\n\n== Efforts to increase female editorship ==\n[[File:Giants in the field of Women in the Arts 2.jpg|thumb|alt=Refer to caption|Attendees at the 2013 Women in the Arts edit-a-thon in Washington, DC]]\n\nDedicated [[edit-a-thon]]s have been organized to increase the coverage of women's topics in Wikipedia and to encourage more women to edit Wikipedia.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://nymag.com/thecut/2014/02/closing-wikipedias-gender-gap-reluctantly.html |title = Closing Wikipedia's Gender Gap \u2014 Reluctantly |work = [[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date = 11 February 2014 |accessdate = 27 August 2014 |author = Stoeffel |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140902160836/http://nymag.com/thecut/2014/02/closing-wikipedias-gender-gap-reluctantly.html |archivedate = 2 September 2014 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> These events are supported by the Wikimedia Foundation, which sometimes provides mentors and technology to help guide newer editors through the process. Recent edit-a-thons have given specific focus to topics such as Australian female neuroscientists and women in Jewish history.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.newstatesman.com/lifestyle/2015/05/wikipedia-has-colossal-problem-women-dont-edit-it |title = The Wikipedia wars: does it matter if our biggest source of knowledge is written by men? |work = newstatesman.com |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150602222518/http://www.newstatesman.com/lifestyle/2015/05/wikipedia-has-colossal-problem-women-dont-edit-it |archivedate = 2 June 2015 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[VisualEditor]], a project funded by the Wikimedia Foundation that allows for [[WYSIWYG]]-style editing on Wikipedia, is said to be aimed in part at closing the gender gap.<ref name=\"Slate Middleton\">{{cite web |url = http://www.slate.com/blogs/future_tense/2012/07/13/kate_middleton_s_wedding_gown_and_wikipedia_s_gender_gap_.html |title = Kate Middleton's wedding gown and Wikipedia's gender gap. |date = 13 July 2012 |accessdate = 4 December 2014 |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141203174753/http://www.slate.com/blogs/future_tense/2012/07/13/kate_middleton_s_wedding_gown_and_wikipedia_s_gender_gap_.html |archivedate = 3 December 2014 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Wikipedia:Teahouse/About|Wikipedia Teahouse]] project was launched with the goal to provide a user-friendly environment for newcomers, with a particular goal of boosting women's participation in Wikipedia.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://dub.washington.edu/pubs/364 |title = Tea & Sympathy: Crafting Positive New User Experiences on Wikipedia |website = washington.edu |publisher = Proc. CSCW \u201813, 23\u2013 27February  2013, San Antonio, Texas, USA |year = 2013 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150209213415/http://dub.washington.edu/pubs/364 |archivedate = 9 February 2015 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, FemTechNet launched \"Wikistorming\" as a project that offers feminist scholarship and encourages Wikipedia editing as part of school and college teaching.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://femtechnet.org/docc/feminist-wiki-storming/|title=feminist wiki-storming \u2013 FemTechNet|access-date=2019-03-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401012841/https://femtechnet.org/docc/feminist-wiki-storming/|archive-date=1 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, the [[National Science Foundation]] announced that it would spend $200,000 to study systemic gender bias on Wikipedia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://freebeacon.com/issues/government-funded-study-why-is-wikipedia-sexist/|title=Government-Funded Study: Why Is Wikipedia Sexist?|author=Elizabeth Harrington|date=30 July 2014|work=[[Washington Free Beacon]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140801062009/http://freebeacon.com/issues/government-funded-study-why-is-wikipedia-sexist/|archivedate=1 August 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAn early-2015 initiative to create a \"women-only\" space for Wikipedia editors was strongly opposed by Wikipedians.<ref>Paling, Emma, \"[https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2015/10/how-wikipedia-is-hostile-to-women/411619/ How Wikipedia Is Hostile to Women] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151021174625/http://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2015/10/how-wikipedia-is-hostile-to-women/411619/|date=21 October 2015}}\", ''[[The Atlantic]]'', 21 October 2015 {{Subscription or advertising}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2015, the WikiProject [[Women in Red]] was launched on the English-language version of Wikipedia, focusing on the creation of new articles about notable women.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/mar/19/women-in-science-on-wikipedia-will-we-ever-fill-the-information-gap|title=Women in science on Wikipedia: will we ever fill the information gap?|author=Redden, Molly|date=19 March 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=16 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108145205/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/mar/19/women-in-science-on-wikipedia-will-we-ever-fill-the-information-gap|archive-date=8 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Mainly through its monthly virtual editathons, Women in Red encourages editors to participate in extending Wikipedia's coverage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsc.org/news-events/community/2017/aug/wikithon/|title=Improving gender balance on Wikipedia|date=21 August 2017|publisher=Royal Society of Chemistry|language=|accessdate=16 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012125221/http://www.rsc.org/news-events/community/2017/aug/wikithon/|archive-date=12 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/life/article/Adding-women-s-voices-to-Wikipedia-12344424.php|title=Wikipedia editing marathons add women's voices to online resource|author=Gordon, Maggie|date=9 November 2017|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|accessdate=16 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816194559/https://www.houstonchronicle.com/life/article/Adding-women-s-voices-to-Wikipedia-12344424.php|archive-date=16 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Thanks in part to the efforts of this project, by June 2018 some 17,000 new women's biographies had been added to Wikipedia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/life/need-close-wikipedias-gender-page-gap/?WT.mc_id=tmg_share_tw|title=Why we need to close Wikipedia's gender page gap|author=Khan, Sadiq|date=12 June 2018|newspaper=The Telegraph|accessdate=16 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816194344/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/life/need-close-wikipedias-gender-page-gap/?WT.mc_id=tmg_share_tw|archive-date=16 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, [[Wikimedia Foundation]] put a funding of $500,000 in building a more encouraging environment for diversity on Wikipedia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foundation.wikimedia.org/wiki/2016-2017_Fundraising_Report|title=2016-2017 Fundraising Report - Wikimedia Foundation Governance Wiki|website=foundation.wikimedia.org|access-date=2019-03-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401042716/https://foundation.wikimedia.org/wiki/2016-2017_Fundraising_Report|archive-date=1 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMany [[WikiProject|Wikiprojects]] are committed to promoting editors' contribution on gender and female studies, which include \"WikiProject women, WikiProject feminism, WikiProject gender studies, and the WikiProject countering systemic bias/gender gap task force\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Kennedy|first1= K. |year=2017|title = Why women should be editing Wikipedia|journal= Women's Studies Journal|volume= 31|issue=1|pages= 94\u201399|oclc= 14929028|issn=0112-4099}}</ref>\n\nExpanding beyond the male/female gender binary, Wikiproject LGBT creates a space for \"re/writing the inclusion and representation of LGBTQ culture into Wikipedia mainspace.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nEdwards (2015) assigns undergraduate students writing assignments to contribute their own findings on the existing gender gap that exist on Wikipedia.  The assignments allow students to incorporate activism within the classroom to support female editorship.  Through classroom facilitation both women and men contribute to expanding female topics.  Edwards believes that through these assignments both sexes will be inspired to alter the current gender gap.<ref>https://www.jstor.org/stable/24810523?Search=yes&resultItemClick=true&searchText=gender&searchText=and&searchText=wikipedia&searchUri=%2Faction%2FdoBasicSearch%3FQuery%3Dgender%2Band%2Bwikipedia%26amp%3Bacc%3Doff%26amp%3Bwc%3Don%26amp%3Bfc%3Doff%26amp%3Bgroup%3Dnone&ab_segments=0%2Fbasic_SYC-5152%2Ftest&refreqid=search%3A7122ee89128ce5e0d98451344f3a5489&seq=2#metadata_info_tab_contents</ref>\n== See also ==\n* [[Racial bias on Wikipedia]]\n* [[Second-generation gender bias]]\n* [[Systemic bias in Wikipedia]]\n* [[Women in Red]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n{{Wikisource|Wikipedia is pushing the boundaries of scholarly practice but the gender gap must be addressed}}\n{{Commons category|Gender bias on Wikipedia}}\n* Edwards, Jennifer C. \"Wiki Women: Bringing Women Into Wikipedia through Activism and Pedagogy.\" The History Teacher, vol. 48, no. 3, 2015, pp. 409\u2013436., [http://www.jstor.org/stable/24810523 online]\n\n=== Media coverage ===\n* {{cite journal |last = Bort |first = Julie |date = 15 February 2014 |title = A Growing Army Of Women Are Taking On Wikipedia's Sexism Problem |url = http://www.businessinsider.com/growing-army-of-women-take-on-wikipedia-2014-2 |journal = Business Insider |volume =  |issue =  |pages =  |doi =  |accessdate = 9 August 2014 }}\n* {{cite news |last = Filipacchi |first = Amanda |date = 24 April 2013 |title = Wikipedia's Sexism Toward Women Novelists |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/28/opinion/sunday/wikipedias-sexism-toward-female-novelists.html |type = op-ed |newspaper = New York Times |location =  |publisher =  |accessdate = }}\n* {{cite journal |last = Filipacchi |first = Amanda |date = 30 April 2013 |title = Sexism on Wikipedia Is Not the Work of 'a Single Misguided Editor' |url = https://www.theatlantic.com/sexes/archive/2013/04/sexism-on-wikipedia-is-not-the-work-of-a-single-misguided-editor/275405/ |journal = The Atlantic |publisher = Atlantic Monthly Group |volume =  |issue =  |pages =  |doi =  |accessdate = 9 August 2014 }}\n* {{cite journal |last = Gleick |first = James |date = 29 April 2013 |title = Wikipedia's Women Problem |url = http://www.nybooks.com/blogs/nyrblog/2013/apr/29/wikipedia-women-problem/ |journal = New York Review of Books |publisher = NYREV |volume =  |issue =  |pages =  |doi =  |accessdate = 19 November 2013 }}\n* {{cite book |last1 = Kloppenburg |first1 = Julia |last2 = Buchem |first2 = Ilona |last3 = Ducki |first3 = Antje |last4 = Khayati |first4 = Sarah |last5 = Weichert |first5 = Nils |year = 2014 |title = Charting Diversity: Working Together Towards Diversity in Wikipedia |url = https://archive.org/details/ChartingDiversity-WorkingTogetherTowardsDiversityInWikipedia |location = Berlin |publisher = Wikimedia Deutschland |page =  |isbn = 978-3-9816799-0-8 |accessdate = 9 August 2014 }}\n* {{cite news |last = Knibbs |first = Kate |date = 10 February 2014 |title = Chipping away at Wikipedia's gender bias, one article at a time |url = http://www.dailydot.com/lifestyle/wikipedia-gender-bias-feminist-editors/ |work = The Daily Dot |accessdate = 30 April 2014 }}\n* {{cite news |last = Leonard |first = Andrew |date = 29 April 2013 |title = Wikipedia's shame: Sexism isn't the problem at the online encyclopedia. The real corruption is the lust for revenge. |url = http://www.salon.com/2013/04/29/wikipedias_shame/ |newspaper =  |location =  |publisher = Salon Media Group |accessdate = 9 August 2014 }}\n* {{cite news |last = Morris |first = Kevin |date = 1 May 2013 |title = Does Wikipedia's sexism problem really prove that the system works? |url = http://www.dailydot.com/society/wikipedia-sexism-problem-sue-gardner/ |work = The Daily Dot |accessdate = 19 November 2013 }}\n* {{cite journal |last = Zandt |first = Deanna |date = 26 April 2013 |title = Yes, Wikipedia is Sexist |url = https://www.forbes.com/sites/deannazandt/2013/04/26/yes-wikipedia-is-sexist-thats-why-it-needs-you/ |journal = Forbes |volume =  |issue =  |pages =  |doi =  |accessdate = 19 November 2013 }}\n* {{cite web |last = Zevallos |first = Zuleyka |date = 8 June 2014 |title = Sexism on Wikipedia: Why the #YesAllWomen Edits Matter |url = http://othersociologist.com/2014/06/08/wikipedia-sexism-yesallwomen/ |website = othersociologist.com |publisher = Zuleyka Zevallos |accessdate = 9 August 2014 }}\n* {{cite news |author = <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date = 2 February 2011 |title = Where Are the Women in Wikipedia? |url = https://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2011/02/02/where-are-the-women-in-wikipedia |newspaper = New York Times |location =  |publisher =  |accessdate = 9 August 2014 }} - Introduction and links to eight opinions.\n* {{cite news |work = [[The Atlantic]] |title = How Wikipedia Is Hostile to Women |date = 21 October 2015 |accessdate = 21 October 2015 |archivedate = 21 October 2015 |url = https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2015/10/how-wikipedia-is-hostile-to-women/411619/ |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151021174625/http://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2015/10/how-wikipedia-is-hostile-to-women/411619/ |first = Emma |last = Paling }}\n\n=== Research and advice ===\n* {{cite web |title = Wikipedia Survey: Overview Results |url = http://www.wikipediasurvey.org/docs/Wikipedia_Overview_15March2010-FINAL.pdf |last1 = Glott |first1 = Ruediger |last2 = Schmidt |first2 = Philipp |last3 = Ghosh |first3 = Rishab |date = March 2010 |website =  |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100414165445/http://wikipediasurvey.org/docs/Wikipedia_Overview_15March2010-FINAL.pdf |archivedate = 14 April 2010 |accessdate = 11 August 2014 }}\n*{{cite web |last1=Klein |first1=Maximilian |display-authors=etal. |title=Monitoring the Gender Gap with Wikidata Human Gender Indicators |url=http://wigi.wmflabs.org/monitoring-gender-gap.pdf|publisher=Cornell University Library |date=10 February 2015}}\n* {{Cite web |last = Tripp |first = Dawn Leonard |title = How to Edit Wikipedia: Lessons from a Female Contributor |work = Anita Borg Institute |accessdate = 6 February 2015 |url = http://anitaborg.org/news/blog/how-to-edit-wikipedia-lessons-from-a-female-contributor/ |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150209033907/http://anitaborg.org/news/blog/how-to-edit-wikipedia-lessons-from-a-female-contributor/ |archive-date = 9 February 2015 |url-status = dead }}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Hinnosaar|first1=Marit|title=Gender Inequality in New Media: Evidence from Wikipedia|journal = Journal of Economic Behavior & Organization |date = July 2019 |pages = 262\u2013276 |volume = 163 |doi = 10.1016/j.jebo.2019.04.020 |url=http://www.carloalberto.org/assets/working-papers/no.411.pdf}}\n*{{cite arXiv|last1=Vitulli|first1=Marie A.|title=Writing Women in Mathematics into Wikipedia |date=20 October 2017 |eprint=1710.11103v3 |class=math.HO}}\n*{{cite arxiv |last1=Wagner |first1=Claudia |last2=Garcia |first2=David |last3=Jadidi |first3=Mohsen |last4=Strohmaier |first4=Markus |year=2015 |title=It's a Man's Wikipedia? Assessing Gender Inequality in an Online Encyclopedia |eprint=1501.06307 |class=cs.CY}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Gender_gap Category:Gender gap] at Wikimedia Meta-Wiki\n* [https://www.academia.edu/41380442/Strangers_in_a_seemingly_open-to-all_website_the_gender_bias_in_Wikipedia Strangers in a seemingly open-to-all website. A research on the gender gap, by Dr. Shlomit Lir] \n{{Wikipedia |state=expanded}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Criticism of Wikipedia]]\n[[Category:Discrimination]]\n[[Category:Gender equality]]\n[[Category:Sexism]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Gender gap problem in Wikipedia and Wikimedia projects}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n'''Gender bias on Wikipedia''' reflects findings that a dominant majority of volunteer Wikipedia editors, particularly on the [[English Wikipedia|English-language site]], are male. Also, there are fewer and less extensive articles about women or topics important to women.\nIt figures among the most frequent [[criticism of Wikipedia|criticisms of Wikipedia]], sometimes as part of a more general criticism about [[systemic bias in Wikipedia]]. The [[Wikimedia Foundation]], which runs Wikipedia, agrees with these criticisms and has made an ongoing attempt to increase female editorship of Wikipedia. [[Edit-a-thon]]s have been held to encourage female editors and increase the coverage of women's topics.<ref name=tnw>{{cite web|url=https://thenextweb.com/tech/2019/03/19/physicist-has-written-over-500-biographies-female-scientists-wikipedia/|website=thenextweb.com|first=Cara|last=Curtis|year=2019|title=This physicist has written over 500 biographies of women scientists on Wikipedia|publisher=[[The Next Web]]|access-date=10 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804235220/https://thenextweb.com/tech/2019/03/19/physicist-has-written-over-500-biographies-female-scientists-wikipedia/|archive-date=4 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=indy500>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/science-women-wikipedia-biography-sexism-academia-physics-a-level-a8773631.html|title=This is why I've written 500 biographies of female scientists on Wikipedia|first=Jessica|last=Wade|date=11 February 2019|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|authorlink=Jess Wade|accessdate=25 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190520230025/https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/science-women-wikipedia-biography-sexism-academia-physics-a-level-a8773631.html|archive-date=20 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Research findings and issues==\nA 2015 survey of contributors to Wikipedia found that less than  15%  of  contributors  were  women. This gender contribution has received significant attention from researchers and the media. A group of researchers and practitioners offered several opinions on why this has been an issue. The gender research literature  suggests that  the  difference  in  contribution  rates  could  be  due  to three factors:  (1) the high levels of conflict in discussions, (2)  dislike  of  critical  environments,  and  (3)  lack  of confidence in editing other contributors' work.<ref>https://dl.acm.org/doi/pdf/10.1145/2145204.2145265</ref><ref name=nytimes20jun2015>{{cite web |author1 = Andrew Lih |title = Can Wikipedia Survive? |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/21/opinion/can-wikipedia-survive.html |website = www.nytimes.com |accessdate = 21 June 2015 |location = Washington |date = 20 June 2015 |quote = ...the considerable and often-noted gender gap among Wikipedia editors; in 2011, less than 15 percent were women. |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150621032208/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/21/opinion/can-wikipedia-survive.html |archivedate = 21 June 2015 |df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=EditorSurveys>Statistics based on Wikimedia Foundation Wikipedia editor surveys [https://wikimediafoundation.org/w/index.php?title=File%3AEditor_Survey_Report_-_April_2011.pdf&page=1 2011] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170702163818/https://wikimediafoundation.org/w/index.php?title=File%3AEditor_Survey_Report_-_April_2011.pdf&page=1 |date=2 July 2017 }} (Nov. 2010-April 2011) and [http://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Research:Wikipedia_Editors_Survey_November_2011 November 2011] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605124632/https://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Research:Wikipedia_Editors_Survey_November_2011 |date=5 June 2016 }} (April \u2013 October 2011)</ref><ref name=PLOS>{{cite journal |last1 = Hill |first1 = Benjamin Mako |last2 = Shaw |first2 = Aaron |last3 = S\u00e1nchez |first3 = Angel |title = The Wikipedia Gender Gap Revisited: Characterizing Survey Response Bias with Propensity Score Estimation |journal = PLoS ONE |date = 26 June 2013 |volume = 8 |issue = 6 |pages = e65782 |doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0065782 |pmid = 23840366 |pmc = 3694126 |bibcode = 2013PLoSO...865782H |df = dmy-all }}</ref> Consequently, Wikipedia has been criticized by some academics and journalists for having primarily male contributors,<ref name=Cohen110130 /><ref>{{cite web |url = http://firstmonday.org/article/view/4291/3381 |title = \"Free as in sexist?\": Free culture and the gender gap |work = [[First Monday (journal)|First Monday]] |accessdate = 10 October 2015 |author = Reagle, Joseph |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150520205049/http://firstmonday.org/article/view/4291/3381 |archivedate = 20 May 2015 |df = dmy-all |author-link = Joseph Reagle }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://surprisinglyfree.com/2013/02/26/joseph-reagle-2/ |title = Joseph Reagle on the gender gap in geek culture |date = 26 February 2013 |accessdate = 10 October 2015 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151117015917/http://surprisinglyfree.com/2013/02/26/joseph-reagle-2/ |archivedate = 17 November 2015 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> and for having fewer and less extensive articles about women or topics important to women. ''[[The New York Times]]'' pointed out that Wikipedia's female participation rate may be in line with other \"public thought-leadership forums\".<ref name=Cohen110130 /> In 2009, a Wikimedia Foundation survey revealed that 6% of editors who made more than 500 edits were female, with the average male editor having twice as many edits.<ref name=Clubhouse>{{cite web |url = http://www-users.cs.umn.edu/~lam/papers/wp-gender-wikisym2011.pdf |title = WP:Clubhouse? An Exploration of Wikipedia's Gender Imbalance |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150418072510/http://www-users.cs.umn.edu/~lam/papers/wp-gender-wikisym2011.pdf |archivedate = 18 April 2015 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn the English Wikipedia and five other language editions that were studied by researchers, the ratio of articles about women to articles about men was higher than in three other databases. However, analysis with computational linguistics concluded that the way women and men are described in articles demonstrates bias, with articles about women more likely to use more words relating to gender and family. The researchers believe that this is a sign Wikipedia editors consider male the \"null gender\" (in other words, that \"male\" is assumed unless otherwise specified, an example of [[male as norm]]).<ref>{{Cite news |url = https://www.technologyreview.com/s/534616/computational-linguistics-reveals-how-wikipedia-articles-are-biased-against-women/ |title = Computational Linguistics Reveals How Wikipedia Articles Are Biased Against Women |last = arXiv |first = Emerging Technology from the |work = MIT Technology Review |access-date = 21 August 2017 |archive-url = https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20170927024309/https://www.technologyreview.com/s/534616/computational-linguistics-reveals-how-wikipedia-articles-are-biased-against-women/ |archive-date = 27 September 2017 |url-status = live }}</ref> Another critique of Wikipedia's approach, from a 2014 ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' editorial, is that it has difficulty making judgments about \"what matters\". To illustrate this point they noted that [[List of pornographic actresses by decade|the page listing pornographic actresses]] was better organized than [[List of women writers|the page listing women writers]].<ref name=GuardianAugust2014>''[[The Guardian]]'' 2014 (London) [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/aug/07/guardian-view-wikipedia-evolving-truth The Guardian view on Wikipedia: evolving truth] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112212758/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/aug/07/guardian-view-wikipedia-evolving-truth |date=12 November 2016 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none;\"\n|+ style=\"text-align: left; font-weight: normal; font-size: 80%\" | Comparison of results for the proportion of Wikipedia readers and editors from the nationally representative Pew survey and the WMF/UNU-MERIT survey (UNU) for a series of dichotomous variables in both surveys. Adjusted numbers for editors assume that response bias for editors is identical to observed response bias for readers and, in the rightmost column, that bias is stable for editors outside the United States. Table reproduced from <ref name=\"PLOS\" />.\n! Variable\n! Readers US (Pew)\n! Readers US (UNU)\n! Editors US (UNU)\n! Editors US Adj.\n! Editors (UNU)\n! Editors Adj.\n|-\n| female\n| 49.0\n| 39.9\n| 17.8\n| 22.7\n| 12.7\n| 16.1\n|-\n| married\n| 60.1\n| 44.1\n| 30.9\n| 36.3\n| 33.2\n| 38.4\n|-\n| children\n| 36.0\n| 29.4\n| 16.4\n| 27.6\n| 14.4\n| 25.3\n|-\n| immigrant\n| 10.1\n| 14.4\n| 12.1\n| 9.8\n| 8.2\n| 7.4\n|-\n| student\n| 17.7\n| 29.9\n| 46.0\n| 38.5\n| 47.7\n| 40.3\n|}\n\nIn 2010, [[United Nations University]] and [[UNU-MERIT]] jointly presented an overview of the results of a global Wikipedia survey.<ref name=WPSurvey2010>{{cite web |title = Wikipedia Survey: Overview Results |url = http://www.wikipediasurvey.org/docs/Wikipedia_Overview_15March2010-FINAL.pdf |last1 = Glott |first1 = Ruediger |last2 = Schmidt |first2 = Philipp |last3 = Ghosh |first3 = Rishab |date = March 2010 |website =  |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100414165445/http://wikipediasurvey.org/docs/Wikipedia_Overview_15March2010-FINAL.pdf |archivedate = 14 April 2010 |accessdate = 11 August 2014 }}</ref> A 30 January 2011, ''New York Times'' article cited this [[Wikimedia Foundation]] collaboration, which indicated that fewer than 13% of contributors to Wikipedia are women.  [[Sue Gardner]], then executive director of the foundation, said that increasing diversity was about making the encyclopedia \"as good as it could be\". Factors the article cited as possibly discouraging women from editing included the \"obsessive fact-loving realm\", associations with the \"hard-driving hacker crowd\", and the necessity to be \"open to very difficult, high-conflict people, even misogynists\".<ref name=Cohen110130>{{cite news |last = Cohen |first = Noam |date = 30 January 2011 |title = Define Gender Gap? Look Up Wikipedia's Contributor List |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/31/business/media/31link.html |newspaper = New York Times |accessdate = 31 January 2011 |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110203043906/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/31/business/media/31link.html |archivedate = 3 February 2011 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> In 2013, the results of the survey were challenged by Hill and Shaw using corrective estimation techniques to suggest upward corrections to the data from the survey and to recommend updates to the statistics being surveyed, giving 22.7% for adult US female editors and 16.1% overall.<ref name=PLOS />\n\nIn February 2011, ''The New York Times'' followed up with a series of opinions on the subject under the banner, \"Where Are the Women in Wikipedia?\"<ref name=WhereAretheWomen>{{cite news |author = <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date = 2 February 2011 |title = Where Are the Women in Wikipedia? |url = https://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2011/02/02/where-are-the-women-in-wikipedia |newspaper = New York Times |accessdate = 9 August 2014 |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140715112226/http://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2011/02/02/where-are-the-women-in-wikipedia |archivedate = 15 July 2014 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> [[Susan Herring|Susan C. Herring]], a professor of information science and linguistics, said that she was not surprised by the Wikipedia contributors' gender gap. She said that the often contentious nature of Wikipedia article \"talk\" pages, where article content is discussed, is unappealing to many women, \"if not outright intimidating\".<ref name=Herring110204>{{cite news |last = Herring |first = Susan C. |date = 4 February 2011 |title = Communication Styles Make a Difference |url = https://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2011/02/02/where-are-the-women-in-wikipedia/communication-styles-make-a-difference |type = opinion |newspaper = New York Times |accessdate = 11 August 2014 |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140724050237/http://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2011/02/02/where-are-the-women-in-wikipedia/communication-styles-make-a-difference |archivedate = 24 July 2014 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> [[Joseph Reagle|Joseph M. Reagle]] reacted similarly, saying that the combination of a \"culture of hacker elitism\", combined with the disproportionate effect of high-conflict members (a minority) on the community atmosphere, can make it unappealing. He said, \"the ideology and rhetoric of freedom and openness can then be used (a) to suppress concerns about inappropriate or offensive speech as \"censorship\" and (b) to rationalize low female participation as simply a matter of their personal preference and choice.\"<ref name=Reagle110204>{{cite news |last = Reagle |first = Joseph M. |date = 4 February 2011 |title = 'Open' Doesn't Include Everyone |url = https://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2011/02/02/where-are-the-women-in-wikipedia/open-doesnt-include-everyone |type = opinion |newspaper = New York Times |accessdate = 11 August 2014 |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140715113229/http://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2011/02/02/where-are-the-women-in-wikipedia/open-doesnt-include-everyone |archivedate = 15 July 2014 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> [[Justine Cassell]] said that although women are as knowledgeable as men, and as able to defend their point of view, \"it is still the case in American society that debate, contention, and vigorous defense of one\u2019s position is often still seen as a male stance, and women\u2019s use of these speech styles can call forth negative evaluations.\"<ref name=Cassell110204>{{cite news |last = Cassell |first = Justine |date = 4 February 2011 |title = Editing Wars Behind the Scenes |url = https://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2011/02/02/where-are-the-women-in-wikipedia/a-culture-of-editing-wars |type = opinion |newspaper = New York Times |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170227113525/http://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2011/02/02/where-are-the-women-in-wikipedia/a-culture-of-editing-wars |archivedate = 27 February 2017 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n{{external media |width=220px | float=right |header-image=[[File:WP BOLD.jpg|220px|link=|alt=]] |video1=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=of93QwXixJg Research proves gender imbalance on Wikipedia], 2:45, [[University of Minnesota]]<ref name=\"UofM\">{{cite web |title=University of Minnesota researchers reveal Wikipedia gender biases |publisher=[[University of Minnesota]] |url=https://cse.umn.edu/news-release/university-of-minnesota-researchers-reveal-wikipedia-gender-biases/ |access-date=21 November 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161208081140/https://cse.umn.edu/news-release/university-of-minnesota-researchers-reveal-wikipedia-gender-biases/ |archive-date=8 December 2016 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|video2=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VZisBB3N4gg Where Are All the Women? Wikipedia\u2019s Gender Gap], 1:12:40, [[West Virginia University]]<ref name=\"WVU\">{{cite web |title=Tackling Wikipedia's Gender Gap |publisher=[[West Virginia University]] |url=http://reedcollegeofmedia.wvu.edu/about/featured-events/wiki-panel |access-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307141703/http://reedcollegeofmedia.wvu.edu/about/featured-events/wiki-panel |archive-date=7 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n}}\nThe ''[[International Journal of Communication]]'' published research by Reagle and Lauren Rhue that examined the coverage, gender representation, and article length of thousands of biographical subjects on the English-language Wikipedia and the online ''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica''. They concluded that Wikipedia provided better coverage and longer articles in general, that Wikipedia typically has more articles on women than ''Britannica'' in absolute terms, but Wikipedia articles on women were more likely to be missing than articles on men relative to ''Britannica''. That is, Wikipedia dominated ''Britannica'' in biographical coverage, but more so when it comes to men. Similarly, one might say that ''Britannica'' is more balanced in whom it neglects to cover than Wikipedia. For both reference works, article length did not consistently differ by gender.<ref name=\"Reagle-Rhue\">{{cite journal |last1 = Reagle |first1 = Joseph |last2 = Rhue |first2 = Lauren |title = Gender Bias in Wikipedia and ''Britannica'' |url = http://ijoc.org/index.php/ijoc/article/viewFile/777/631 |year = 2011 |journal = International Journal of Communication |volume = 5 |publisher = Joseph Reagle & Lauren Rhue |pages = 1138\u20131158 |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160322081809/http://ijoc.org/index.php/ijoc/article/viewFile/777/631 |archivedate = 22 March 2016 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2011, the Wikimedia Foundation conducted its first semi-annual Wikipedia survey. It suggested that 9% of Wikipedia editors are women. It also reported, \"Contrary to the perception of some, our data shows that very few women editors feel like they have been harassed, and very few feel Wikipedia is a sexualized environment.\"<ref name=WES2011>{{cite web |url = https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/76/Editor_Survey_Report_-_April_2011.pdf |title = Wikipedia Editors Study: Results From ''The Editor Survey, April 2011'' |date = April 2011 |website = [[Wikipedia]] |accessdate = 18 May 2014 |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141226041321/http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/76/Editor_Survey_Report_-_April_2011.pdf |archivedate = 26 December 2014 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> However, an October 2011 paper at the [[WikiSym|International Symposium on Wikis and Open Collaboration]] found evidence that suggested that Wikipedia may have \"a culture that may be resistant to female participation\".<ref name=WPClubhouse>{{cite conference |last1 = Lam |first1 = Shyong K. |last2 = Uduwage |first2 = Anuradha |last3 = Dong |first3 = Zhenhua |last4 = Sen |first4 = Shilad |last5 = Musicant |first5 = David R. |last6 = Terveen |first6 = Loren |last7 = Reidl |first7 = John |date = October 2011 |title = WP:Clubhouse? An Exploration of Wikipedia's Gender Imbalance |url = http://files.grouplens.org/papers/wp-gender-wikisym2011.pdf |conference = WikiSym'11 |conference-url = http://www.wikisym.org/ws2011/ |publisher = ACM |authorlink6 = Loren Terveen |authorlink7 = John T. Riedl |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131029232437/http://files.grouplens.org/papers/wp-gender-wikisym2011.pdf |archivedate = 29 October 2013 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nA study published in 2014 found that there is also an \"Internet skills gap\" with regard to Wikipedia editors. The authors found that the most likely Wikipedia contributors are high-skilled men and that there is no gender gap among low-skilled editors, and concluded that the \"skills gap\" exacerbates the gender gap among editors.<ref>{{cite journal |last1 = Hargittai |first1 = Eszter |last2 = Shaw |first2 = Aaron |title = Mind the skills gap: the role of Internet know-how and gender in differentiated contributions to Wikipedia |journal = Information, Communication & Society |date = 4 November 2014 |pages = 424\u2013442 |doi = 10.1080/1369118X.2014.957711 |volume = 18 |issue = 4 }}</ref> During 2010\u201314, women made up 61% of participants of the college courses arranged by the Wiki Education Foundation program that included editing Wikipedia as part of the curriculum. Their contributions were found to shift the Wikipedia content from pop-culture and [[Science, technology, engineering, and mathematics|STEM]] towards social sciences and humanities.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.sacbee.com/2014/09/23/6727564/bruce-maiman-wikipedia-grows-up.html |title = Wikipedia grows up on college campuses |author = Bruce Maiman |date = 23 September 2014 |website = [[The Sacramento Bee]] |accessdate = 23 September 2014 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140923224639/http://www.sacbee.com/2014/09/23/6727564/bruce-maiman-wikipedia-grows-up.html |archivedate = 23 September 2014 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Wagner et al.<ref>{{cite journal |last1 = Wagner |first1 = Claudia |last2 = Graells-Garrido |first2 = Eduardo |last3 = Garcia |first3 = David |last4 = Menczer |first4 = Filippo |title = Women through the glass ceiling: gender asymmetries in Wikipedia |journal = EPJ Data Science |date = 1 March 2016 |doi = 10.1140/epjds/s13688-016-0066-4 |volume = 5 |number = 5|arxiv = 1601.04890 }}</ref> found that gender inequality manifests itself in Wikipedia's biographical content in multiple ways, including unequal thresholds for determining a subject's notability, topical bias, linguistic bias, and structural inequalities. The authors found that when editors determine if a subject is notable enough to include on Wikipedia, they hold women to a higher standard of notability, resulting in women on Wikipedia being slightly more notable than men on Wikipedia. As for topical bias, biographies about women tend to focus more on family-, gender-, and relationship-related topics. This is especially true for biographies of women born before 1900. The authors also found structural differences in terms of meta-data and hyperlinks, which have consequences for information-seeking activities.\n\nA 2017 study found that women participating in an experiment by editing a Wikipedia-like site tended to view other editors as male, and to view their responses as more critical than if the other editor was [[gender-neutral]]. The study concluded that:<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shane-Simpson |first1=Christina |last2=Gillespie-Lynch |first2=Kristen |title=Examining potential mechanisms underlying the Wikipedia gender gap through a collaborative editing task |journal=[[Computers in Human Behavior]] |date=January 2017 |volume=66 |pages=312\u2013328 |doi=10.1016/j.chb.2016.09.043 |url=https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-01612306/document |access-date=4 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181104170109/https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-01612306/document |archive-date=4 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{quote |text = ...visible female editors on Wikipedia and broader encouragement of the use of constructive feedback may begin to alleviate the Wikipedia gender gap. Furthermore, the relatively high proportion of anonymous editors may exacerbate the Wikipedia gender gap, as anonymity may often be perceived as male and more critical.}}\n\nA study by Ford and Wajcman observes that research on the gender bias continues to frame the problem as a deficit in women. In contrast, their central argument states that infrastructure studies in [[feminist technoscience]] allows the gender analysis to be taken to a further level. It looks at three issues within the infrastructure: content policies, software, and the legalistic framework of operation. It suggests that progress can be made through altering that culture of [[knowledge production]] through encouraging alternate knowledge, reducing the technical barriers to editing, and addressing the complexity of Wikipedia policies.<ref>{{cite journal |last1 = Ford |first1 = Heather |last2 = Wajcman |first2 = Judy |title = 'Anyone can edit', not everyone does: Wikipedia and the gender gap |journal = Social Studies of Science |date = 2017 |url = http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/68675/ |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20161228081909/http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/68675/ |archivedate = 28 December 2016 |df = dmy-all | doi = 10.1177/0306312717692172 |pmid = 28791929 |volume=47 |issue = 4 |pages=511\u2013527}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, in the Pipeline of Online Participation Inequalities, Shaw and Hargittai concluded from their studies that to solve the problems of participation inequality including gender bias requires a broader focus on subjects other than inequality.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite journal|last=Shaw|first=Aaron|last2=Hargittai|first2=Eszter|date=2018-02-01|title=The Pipeline of Online Participation Inequalities: The Case of Wikipedia Editing|journal=Journal of Communication|volume=68|issue=1|pages=143\u2013168|doi=10.1093/joc/jqx003|issn=0021-9916}}</ref> They recommended a focus on encouraging participants of all educational backgrounds, skill levels, and age groups will help Wikipedia to improve. They recommended further that informing more women that Wikipedia is free to edit and open to everyone is critical in eliminating gender bias.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nIn March 2018, mathematician [[Marie A. Vitulli]] wrote in ''[[Notices of the American Mathematical Society]]'', \"The percentage of women editors on Wikipedia remains dismally low.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.ams.org/journals/notices/201803/rnoti-p330.pdf|title=Writing Women in Mathematics into Wikipedia 65 (3). pp. 331\u2013332. doi:10.1090/noti1650|last=Vitulli|first=Marie A.|date=March 2018|publisher=Notices of the American Mathematical Society|access-date=11 October 2018|doi=10.1090/noti1650|journal=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303142204/http://www.ams.org/journals/notices/201803/rnoti-p330.pdf|archive-date=3 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, when [[Donna Strickland]] won a [[Nobel Prize in Physics]], numerous write-ups mentioned that she did not previously have a Wikipedia page. A draft had been submitted, but was rejected for not demonstrating \"significant coverage (not just passing mentions) about the subject\".<ref>{{cite web |title=The Nobel prize winning scientist who wasn't famous enough for Wikipedia |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/people/the-nobel-prize-winning-scientist-who-wasn-t-famous-enough-for-wikipedia-1.3650212 |website=[[The Irish Times]] |accessdate=3 October 2018 |date=3 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003152517/https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/people/the-nobel-prize-winning-scientist-who-wasn-t-famous-enough-for-wikipedia-1.3650212 |archive-date=3 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/live/2018/oct/02/nobel-prize-in-physics-2018-live|title=Nobel physics prize winners include first female laureate for 55 years \u2013 as it happened|first=Nicola|last=Davis|date=2 October 2018|accessdate=27 February 2019|work=The Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190226083859/https://www.theguardian.com/science/live/2018/oct/02/nobel-prize-in-physics-2018-live|archive-date=26 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Leyland Cecco|title=Female Nobel prize winner deemed not important enough for Wikipedia entry|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2018/oct/03/donna-strickland-nobel-physics-prize-wikipedia-denied|work=The Guardian|date=2018-10-03|access-date=2018-10-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003195646/https://www.theguardian.com/science/2018/oct/03/donna-strickland-nobel-physics-prize-wikipedia-denied|archive-date=3 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Noopur Raval, a PhD candidate at UC Irvine, wrote in The Encyclopedia Must Fail!- Notes on Queering Wikipedia, that \"making a platform open access does not automatically translate to equality of participation, ease of access, or cultural acceptance of the medium.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Noopur|first=Raval|title=The Encyclopedia Must Fail! \u2013 Notes on Queering Wikipedia|url=https://adanewmedia.org/2014/07/issue5-raval/|journal=Ada: A Journal of Gender, New Media, and Technology|issue=\"5\"|doi=10.7264/N37W69GC|issn=2325-0496|year=2014|access-date=14 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014030644/https://adanewmedia.org/2014/07/issue5-raval/|archive-date=14 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2017, researchers Matthew A. Vetter and Keon Mandell Pettiway explain that the white, cis-gendered male dominance amongst Wikipedia editors has led to the \"erasure of non-normative gender and sexual identities,\" in addition to cis-gendered females. The \"androcentric and heteronormative discourses\" of Wikipedia editing insufficiently allow \"marginalized gender and sexual identities to take part in language use and the construction of knowledge.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|url=https://tcjournal.org/vol7/hacking-hetero-normative-logics|title=Hacking Hetero/Normative Logics: Queer Feminist Media Praxis in Wikipedia |journal= Technoculture|last=Matthew|first=Vetter|last2=Pettiway|first2=Keon|date=20 November 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014030646/https://tcjournal.org/vol7/hacking-hetero-normative-logics|archive-date=14 October 2019|access-date=2019-10-14|volume=7}}</ref>\n\n== Possible causes ==\n[[File:Sue Gardner Feb 2013 portrait crop 2.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Sue Gardner street portrait|Former Wikimedia Foundation executive director [[Sue Gardner]] provided nine reasons, offered by female [[Wikipedia editors]], \"Why Women Don't Edit Wikipedia.\"<ref name=Gardner110219 />]]\n\nSeveral causes for this gender disparity have been suggested. A 2010 study revealed a Wikipedia female participation rate of 13 percent, observed to be close to the 15 percent overall female participation rate of other \"public thought-leadership forums\".<ref name=Cohen110130 /><ref name=\"Signpost-2013-07-31\">{{cite web |url = https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Wikipedia_Signpost/2013-07-31/Recent_research |title = Recent research&nbsp;\u2014 Napoleon, Michael Jackson and Srebrenica across cultures, 90% of Wikipedia better than Britannica, WikiSym preview |last = Yasseri |first = Taha |last2 = Liao |first2 = Han-Teng |last3 = Konieczny |first3 = Piotr |last4 = Morgan |first4 = Jonathan |last5 = Bayer |first5 = Tilman |date = 31 July 2013 |work = [[Wikipedia:Wikipedia Signpost|The Signpost]] |publisher = [[Wikipedia]] |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150617074727/https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Wikipedia_Signpost/2013-07-31/Recent_research |archivedate = 17 June 2015 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> Wikipedia research fellow Sarah Stierch acknowledged that it is \"fairly common\" for Wikipedia contributors to remain gender-anonymous.<ref name=\"DailyDotStierch\">{{cite web |url = http://www.dailydot.com/society/wikipedia-gender-gap-sarah-stierch/ |title = The women of Wikipedia: Closing the site's giant gender gap |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150703203120/http://www.dailydot.com/society/wikipedia-gender-gap-sarah-stierch/ |archivedate = 3 July 2015 |df = dmy-all |date = 24 January 2013 }}</ref> A perceived unwelcoming culture and tolerance of violent and abusive language are also reasons put forth for the gender gap.<ref name=\"CSM-misogyny\">{{cite journal |url = http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Security-Watch/Backchannels/2013/0801/In-UK-rising-chorus-of-outrage-over-online-misogyny |title = In UK, rising chorus of outrage over online misogyny |journal = Christian Science Monitor |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150704200524/http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Security-Watch/Backchannels/2013/0801/In-UK-rising-chorus-of-outrage-over-online-misogyny |archivedate = 4 July 2015 |df = dmy-all |date = August 2013 }}</ref> According to a 2013 study,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url = http://dub.washington.edu/djangosite/media/papers/morgan_cscw2013_final.pdf |title = Tea & Sympathy: Crafting Positive New User Experiences on Wikipedia |author = Jonathan T. Morgan |author2 = Siko Bouterse |author3 = Sarah Stierch |author4 = Heather Walls |publisher = Wikimedia Foundation |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141105195335/http://dub.washington.edu/djangosite/media/papers/morgan_cscw2013_final.pdf |archivedate = 5 November 2014 |df = dmy-all |access-date = 24 August 2014 }}</ref> another cause of the gender gap in Wikipedia is the failure to attract and retain female editors, resulting in a negative impact on Wikipedia's coverage. As well, Wikipedia \"...editors that publicly identify as women face harassment\" from other Wikipedia editors.<ref name=\"Montellaro\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2015/11/how-does-political-pedia-stay-apolitical/450948/ |title=How Does Political Wikipedia Stay Apolitical?: The seventh-most visited site is one of the first online listings for any elected official\u2014but how does a site that stakes its reputation on neutrality walk that line |last=Montellaro |first=Zach |date=18 November 2015 |website=theatlantic.com |publisher=[[The Atlantic]] |access-date =20 August 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821004146/https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2015/11/how-does-political-wikipedia-stay-apolitical/450948/ |archive-date=21 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFormer Wikimedia Foundation executive director [[Sue Gardner]] cited nine reasons why women don't edit Wikipedia, culled from comments by female [[Wikipedia community|Wikipedia editors]]:<ref name=Gardner110219>{{cite web |last = Gardner |first = Sue |date = 19 February 2011 |title = Nine Reasons Why Women Don't Edit Wikipedia, In Their Own Words |url = http://suegardner.org/2011/02/19/nine-reasons-why-women-dont-edit-wikipedia-in-their-own-words/ |type = blog |website = suegardner.org |accessdate =  |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150718103642/http://suegardner.org/2011/02/19/nine-reasons-why-women-dont-edit-wikipedia-in-their-own-words/ |archive-date = 18 July 2015 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n# A lack of [[user-friendliness]] in the [[User interface|editing interface]] \n# Not having enough [[free time]] \n# A lack of [[self-confidence]]  \n# [[Conflict avoidance|Aversion to conflict]] and an unwillingness to participate in lengthy [[Criticism of Wikipedia#Level of debate, edit wars and harassment|edit wars]]  \n# Belief that their contributions are too likely to be reverted or deleted  \n# Some find its overall atmosphere [[Misogyny|misogynistic]] \n# Wikipedia culture is sexual in ways they find off-putting\n# Being addressed as male is off-putting to women whose primary language has grammatical gender\n# Fewer opportunities than other sites for social relationships and a welcoming tone\n\nThough the proportion of female readership to male readership on Wikipedia is roughly equal (47%), females are less likely to convert themselves to editors (16%). Several studies suggest that there may be a formed culture in Wikipedia that discourages women from participating.<ref name=\"WPClubhouse3\">{{cite conference|last1=Lam|first1=Shyong K.|last2=Uduwage|first2=Anuradha|last3=Dong|first3=Zhenhua|last4=Sen|first4=Shilad|last5=Musicant|first5=David R.|last6=Terveen|first6=Loren|authorlink6=Loren Terveen|last7=Reidl|first7=John|authorlink7=John T. Riedl|date=October 2011|title=WP:Clubhouse? An Exploration of Wikipedia's Gender Imbalance|url=http://files.grouplens.org/papers/wp-gender-wikisym2011.pdf|url-status=live|conference=WikiSym'11|publisher=ACM|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029232437/http://files.grouplens.org/papers/wp-gender-wikisym2011.pdf|archivedate=29 October 2013|conference-url=http://www.wikisym.org/ws2011/|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\":04\">{{Cite journal|last=Collier|first=Benjamin|last2=Bear|first2=Julia|date=2012|title=Conflict, criticism, or confidence: an empirical examination of the gender gap in wikipedia contributions|url=http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?doid=2145204.2145265|journal=Proceedings of the ACM 2012 Conference on Computer Supported Cooperative Work - CSCW '12|location=Seattle, Washington, USA|publisher=ACM Press|pages=383|doi=10.1145/2145204.2145265|isbn=9781450310864|access-date=1 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325090443/https://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?doid=2145204.2145265|archive-date=25 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Lam ''et al''. link this culture due to a disparity in male-to-female centric topics represented and edited, the tendency for female users to be more active in the social and community aspects of Wikipedia, an increased likelihood that edits by new female editors are reverted, and/or that articles with high proportions of female editors are more contentious.<ref name=\"WPClubhouse3\" />\n\nCollier and Bear in 2012 summarized the reason for working barriers of women in Wikipedia in three words: conflict, criticism and confidence. Conflict means [[online harassment]], [[trolling]] and competition which women generally do not like; Criticism refers to women's unwillingness to edit someone else's work and to let their work be edited by someone else; Confidence shows that women are often not too confident about their own expertise and ability in editing and contributing to a certain work.<ref name=\":04\" /> Wikipedia's free to edit policy gives Internet users an open platform, while also unconsciously breeding a competitive and critical environment that limits women's incentives to participate.\n\nThrough examining the power infrastructure of Wikipedia, Ford and Wajcman pointed out another cause that may reinforce Wikipedia's gender bias. Editing on Wikipedia requires \"particular forms of [[Sociotechnical system|sociotechnical]] expertise and authority that constitute the knowledge or [[epistemological]] infrastructure of Wikipedia\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ford|first=Heather|last2=Wajcman|first2=Judy|date=August 2017|title='Anyone can edit', not everyone does: Wikipedia's infrastructure and the gender gap|journal=Social Studies of Science|volume=47|issue=4|pages=511\u2013527|doi=10.1177/0306312717692172|pmid=28791929|issn=0306-3127|url=http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/68675/1/Wajcman_Anyone%20can%20edit_Final_2017.pdf|access-date=8 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919063205/http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/68675/1/Wajcman_Anyone%20can%20edit_Final_2017.pdf|archive-date=19 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>  People who are equipped with this expertise and skill are considered more likely to reach positions with power in Wikipedia. These are proposed to be predominantly men.\n\nStudies have also considered the gender bias in Wikipedia from a historical perspective. Konieczny and Klein indicated that Wikipedia is just a part of our biased society which has a long history of [[gender inequality]].<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Konieczny|first=Piotr|last2=Klein|first2=Maximilian|date=December 2018|title=Gender gap through time and space: A journey through Wikipedia biographies via the Wikidata Human Gender Indicator|journal=New Media & Society|volume=20|issue=12|pages=4608\u20134633|doi=10.1177/1461444818779080|issn=1461-4448}}</ref> As Wikipedia records daily activities by individual editors, it serves as both \"a reflection of the world\" and \"a tool used to produce our world\".<ref name=\":12\" /> Even though gender bias is reducing slowly, it remains an existing problem.\n\n== Reactions ==\n\nThe [[Wikimedia Foundation]] has officially held, since at least 2011 when Gardner was executive director, that gender bias exists in the project. It has made some attempts to address it but Gardner has expressed frustration with the degree of success achieved. She has also noted that \"in the very limited leisure time women had, they tended to be more involved in social activities instead of editing Wikipedia. 'Women see technology more as a tool they use to accomplish tasks, rather than something fun in itself.{{'\"}}<ref name=Huang130811>{{cite news |last = Huang |first = Keira |date = 11 August 2013 |title = Wikipedia fails to bridge gender gap |url = http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/article/1295872/wikipedia-fails-bridge-gender-gap |newspaper = South China Morning Post |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160115195821/http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/article/1295872/wikipedia-fails-bridge-gender-gap |archivedate = 15 January 2016 |df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=Wikistorm2013>{{cite web |url = http://femtechnet.newschool.edu/wikistorming/ |title = Wikistorming |date = Fall 2013 |website = FemTechNet |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150717034630/http://femtechnet.newschool.edu/wikistorming/ |archivedate = 17 July 2015 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> In 2011, the Foundation set a target of having 25 percent of its contributors identifying as female by 2015.<ref name=Cohen110130 /> In August 2013, Gardner said, \"I didn't solve it. We didn't solve it. The Wikimedia Foundation didn't solve it. The solution won't come from the Wikimedia Foundation.\"<ref name=Huang130811 />\n\nWriting for ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' in 2011, [[Heather Mac Donald]] called Wikipedia's gender imbalance a \"non-problem in search of a misguided solution.\" Mac Donald asserted, \"The most straightforward explanation for the differing rates of participation in Wikipedia\u2014and the one that conforms to everyday experience\u2014is  that, on average, males and females have different interests and preferred ways of spending their free time.\"<ref>{{cite web |last = Mac Donald |first = Heather |url = http://www.slate.com/articles/double_x/doublex/2011/02/wikipedia_is_maledominated_that_doesnt_mean_its_sexist.html |title = Wikipedia Is Male-Dominated. That Doesn't Mean It's Sexist. |website = [[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |date = 9 February 2011 |accessdate = 7 January 2015 |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150107205929/http://www.slate.com/articles/double_x/doublex/2011/02/wikipedia_is_maledominated_that_doesnt_mean_its_sexist.html |archivedate = 7 January 2015 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, Wikipedia co-founder [[Jimmy Wales]] announced in a BBC interview the [[Wikimedia Foundation]]'s plans for \"doubling down\" on the gender content gap at Wikipedia. Wales said the Foundation would be open to more outreach and more software changes.<ref name=\"BBC\">[https://www.bbc.com/news/business-28701772 Wikipedia 'completely failed' to fix gender imbalance] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161229004148/http://www.bbc.com/news/business-28701772 |date=29 December 2016 }}, [[BBC]] interview with [[Jimmy Wales]], 8 August 2014; starting at 45 seconds.</ref>\n\n== Efforts to increase female editorship ==\n[[File:Giants in the field of Women in the Arts 2.jpg|thumb|alt=Refer to caption|Attendees at the 2013 Women in the Arts edit-a-thon in Washington, DC]]\n\nDedicated [[edit-a-thon]]s have been organized to increase the coverage of women's topics in Wikipedia and to encourage more women to edit Wikipedia.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://nymag.com/thecut/2014/02/closing-wikipedias-gender-gap-reluctantly.html |title = Closing Wikipedia's Gender Gap \u2014 Reluctantly |work = [[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date = 11 February 2014 |accessdate = 27 August 2014 |author = Stoeffel |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140902160836/http://nymag.com/thecut/2014/02/closing-wikipedias-gender-gap-reluctantly.html |archivedate = 2 September 2014 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> These events are supported by the Wikimedia Foundation, which sometimes provides mentors and technology to help guide newer editors through the process. Recent edit-a-thons have given specific focus to topics such as Australian female neuroscientists and women in Jewish history.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.newstatesman.com/lifestyle/2015/05/wikipedia-has-colossal-problem-women-dont-edit-it |title = The Wikipedia wars: does it matter if our biggest source of knowledge is written by men? |work = newstatesman.com |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150602222518/http://www.newstatesman.com/lifestyle/2015/05/wikipedia-has-colossal-problem-women-dont-edit-it |archivedate = 2 June 2015 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[VisualEditor]], a project funded by the Wikimedia Foundation that allows for [[WYSIWYG]]-style editing on Wikipedia, is said to be aimed in part at closing the gender gap.<ref name=\"Slate Middleton\">{{cite web |url = http://www.slate.com/blogs/future_tense/2012/07/13/kate_middleton_s_wedding_gown_and_wikipedia_s_gender_gap_.html |title = Kate Middleton's wedding gown and Wikipedia's gender gap. |date = 13 July 2012 |accessdate = 4 December 2014 |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141203174753/http://www.slate.com/blogs/future_tense/2012/07/13/kate_middleton_s_wedding_gown_and_wikipedia_s_gender_gap_.html |archivedate = 3 December 2014 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Wikipedia:Teahouse/About|Wikipedia Teahouse]] project was launched with the goal to provide a user-friendly environment for newcomers, with a particular goal of boosting women's participation in Wikipedia.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://dub.washington.edu/pubs/364 |title = Tea & Sympathy: Crafting Positive New User Experiences on Wikipedia |website = washington.edu |publisher = Proc. CSCW \u201813, 23\u2013 27February  2013, San Antonio, Texas, USA |year = 2013 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150209213415/http://dub.washington.edu/pubs/364 |archivedate = 9 February 2015 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, FemTechNet launched \"Wikistorming\" as a project that offers feminist scholarship and encourages Wikipedia editing as part of school and college teaching.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://femtechnet.org/docc/feminist-wiki-storming/|title=feminist wiki-storming \u2013 FemTechNet|access-date=2019-03-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401012841/https://femtechnet.org/docc/feminist-wiki-storming/|archive-date=1 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, the [[National Science Foundation]] announced that it would spend $200,000 to study systemic gender bias on Wikipedia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://freebeacon.com/issues/government-funded-study-why-is-wikipedia-sexist/|title=Government-Funded Study: Why Is Wikipedia Sexist?|author=Elizabeth Harrington|date=30 July 2014|work=[[Washington Free Beacon]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140801062009/http://freebeacon.com/issues/government-funded-study-why-is-wikipedia-sexist/|archivedate=1 August 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAn early-2015 initiative to create a \"women-only\" space for Wikipedia editors was strongly opposed by Wikipedians.<ref>Paling, Emma, \"[https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2015/10/how-wikipedia-is-hostile-to-women/411619/ How Wikipedia Is Hostile to Women] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151021174625/http://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2015/10/how-wikipedia-is-hostile-to-women/411619/|date=21 October 2015}}\", ''[[The Atlantic]]'', 21 October 2015 {{Subscription or advertising}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2015, the WikiProject [[Women in Red]] was launched on the English-language version of Wikipedia, focusing on the creation of new articles about notable women.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/mar/19/women-in-science-on-wikipedia-will-we-ever-fill-the-information-gap|title=Women in science on Wikipedia: will we ever fill the information gap?|author=Redden, Molly|date=19 March 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=16 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108145205/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/mar/19/women-in-science-on-wikipedia-will-we-ever-fill-the-information-gap|archive-date=8 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Mainly through its monthly virtual editathons, Women in Red encourages editors to participate in extending Wikipedia's coverage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsc.org/news-events/community/2017/aug/wikithon/|title=Improving gender balance on Wikipedia|date=21 August 2017|publisher=Royal Society of Chemistry|language=|accessdate=16 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012125221/http://www.rsc.org/news-events/community/2017/aug/wikithon/|archive-date=12 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/life/article/Adding-women-s-voices-to-Wikipedia-12344424.php|title=Wikipedia editing marathons add women's voices to online resource|author=Gordon, Maggie|date=9 November 2017|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|accessdate=16 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816194559/https://www.houstonchronicle.com/life/article/Adding-women-s-voices-to-Wikipedia-12344424.php|archive-date=16 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Thanks in part to the efforts of this project, by June 2018 some 17,000 new women's biographies had been added to Wikipedia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/life/need-close-wikipedias-gender-page-gap/?WT.mc_id=tmg_share_tw|title=Why we need to close Wikipedia's gender page gap|author=Khan, Sadiq|date=12 June 2018|newspaper=The Telegraph|accessdate=16 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816194344/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/life/need-close-wikipedias-gender-page-gap/?WT.mc_id=tmg_share_tw|archive-date=16 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, [[Wikimedia Foundation]] put a funding of $500,000 in building a more encouraging environment for diversity on Wikipedia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foundation.wikimedia.org/wiki/2016-2017_Fundraising_Report|title=2016-2017 Fundraising Report - Wikimedia Foundation Governance Wiki|website=foundation.wikimedia.org|access-date=2019-03-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401042716/https://foundation.wikimedia.org/wiki/2016-2017_Fundraising_Report|archive-date=1 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMany [[WikiProject|Wikiprojects]] are committed to promoting editors' contribution on gender and female studies, which include \"WikiProject women, WikiProject feminism, WikiProject gender studies, and the WikiProject countering systemic bias/gender gap task force\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Kennedy|first1= K. |year=2017|title = Why women should be editing Wikipedia|journal= Women's Studies Journal|volume= 31|issue=1|pages= 94\u201399|oclc= 14929028|issn=0112-4099}}</ref>\n\nExpanding beyond the male/female gender binary, Wikiproject LGBT creates a space for \"re/writing the inclusion and representation of LGBTQ culture into Wikipedia mainspace.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nEdwards (2015) assigns undergrad students writing assignments to contribute their own findings on the existing gender gap that exist on Wikipedia.  The assignments allow students to incorporate activism within the classroom to support female editorship.  Through classroom facilitation both women and men contribute to expanding female topics.  Edwards believes that through these assignments both sexes will be inspired to alter the current gender gap.\n  \n<ref>https://www.jstor.org/stable/24810523?Search=yes&resultItemClick=true&searchText=gender&searchText=and&searchText=wikipedia&searchUri=%2Faction%2FdoBasicSearch%3FQuery%3Dgender%2Band%2Bwikipedia%26amp%3Bacc%3Doff%26amp%3Bwc%3Don%26amp%3Bfc%3Doff%26amp%3Bgroup%3Dnone&ab_segments=0%2Fbasic_SYC-5152%2Ftest&refreqid=search%3A7122ee89128ce5e0d98451344f3a5489&seq=2#metadata_info_tab_contents</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Racial bias on Wikipedia]]\n* [[Second-generation gender bias]]\n* [[Systemic bias in Wikipedia]]\n* [[Women in Red]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n{{Wikisource|Wikipedia is pushing the boundaries of scholarly practice but the gender gap must be addressed}}\n{{Commons category|Gender bias on Wikipedia}}\n* Edwards, Jennifer C. \"Wiki Women: Bringing Women Into Wikipedia through Activism and Pedagogy.\" The History Teacher, vol. 48, no. 3, 2015, pp. 409\u2013436., [http://www.jstor.org/stable/24810523 online]\n\n=== Media coverage ===\n* {{cite journal |last = Bort |first = Julie |date = 15 February 2014 |title = A Growing Army Of Women Are Taking On Wikipedia's Sexism Problem |url = http://www.businessinsider.com/growing-army-of-women-take-on-wikipedia-2014-2 |journal = Business Insider |volume =  |issue =  |pages =  |doi =  |accessdate = 9 August 2014 }}\n* {{cite news |last = Filipacchi |first = Amanda |date = 24 April 2013 |title = Wikipedia's Sexism Toward Women Novelists |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/28/opinion/sunday/wikipedias-sexism-toward-female-novelists.html |type = op-ed |newspaper = New York Times |location =  |publisher =  |accessdate = }}\n* {{cite journal |last = Filipacchi |first = Amanda |date = 30 April 2013 |title = Sexism on Wikipedia Is Not the Work of 'a Single Misguided Editor' |url = https://www.theatlantic.com/sexes/archive/2013/04/sexism-on-wikipedia-is-not-the-work-of-a-single-misguided-editor/275405/ |journal = The Atlantic |publisher = Atlantic Monthly Group |volume =  |issue =  |pages =  |doi =  |accessdate = 9 August 2014 }}\n* {{cite journal |last = Gleick |first = James |date = 29 April 2013 |title = Wikipedia's Women Problem |url = http://www.nybooks.com/blogs/nyrblog/2013/apr/29/wikipedia-women-problem/ |journal = New York Review of Books |publisher = NYREV |volume =  |issue =  |pages =  |doi =  |accessdate = 19 November 2013 }}\n* {{cite book |last1 = Kloppenburg |first1 = Julia |last2 = Buchem |first2 = Ilona |last3 = Ducki |first3 = Antje |last4 = Khayati |first4 = Sarah |last5 = Weichert |first5 = Nils |year = 2014 |title = Charting Diversity: Working Together Towards Diversity in Wikipedia |url = https://archive.org/details/ChartingDiversity-WorkingTogetherTowardsDiversityInWikipedia |location = Berlin |publisher = Wikimedia Deutschland |page =  |isbn = 978-3-9816799-0-8 |accessdate = 9 August 2014 }}\n* {{cite news |last = Knibbs |first = Kate |date = 10 February 2014 |title = Chipping away at Wikipedia's gender bias, one article at a time |url = http://www.dailydot.com/lifestyle/wikipedia-gender-bias-feminist-editors/ |work = The Daily Dot |accessdate = 30 April 2014 }}\n* {{cite news |last = Leonard |first = Andrew |date = 29 April 2013 |title = Wikipedia's shame: Sexism isn't the problem at the online encyclopedia. The real corruption is the lust for revenge. |url = http://www.salon.com/2013/04/29/wikipedias_shame/ |newspaper =  |location =  |publisher = Salon Media Group |accessdate = 9 August 2014 }}\n* {{cite news |last = Morris |first = Kevin |date = 1 May 2013 |title = Does Wikipedia's sexism problem really prove that the system works? |url = http://www.dailydot.com/society/wikipedia-sexism-problem-sue-gardner/ |work = The Daily Dot |accessdate = 19 November 2013 }}\n* {{cite journal |last = Zandt |first = Deanna |date = 26 April 2013 |title = Yes, Wikipedia is Sexist |url = https://www.forbes.com/sites/deannazandt/2013/04/26/yes-wikipedia-is-sexist-thats-why-it-needs-you/ |journal = Forbes |volume =  |issue =  |pages =  |doi =  |accessdate = 19 November 2013 }}\n* {{cite web |last = Zevallos |first = Zuleyka |date = 8 June 2014 |title = Sexism on Wikipedia: Why the #YesAllWomen Edits Matter |url = http://othersociologist.com/2014/06/08/wikipedia-sexism-yesallwomen/ |website = othersociologist.com |publisher = Zuleyka Zevallos |accessdate = 9 August 2014 }}\n* {{cite news |author = <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date = 2 February 2011 |title = Where Are the Women in Wikipedia? |url = https://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2011/02/02/where-are-the-women-in-wikipedia |newspaper = New York Times |location =  |publisher =  |accessdate = 9 August 2014 }} - Introduction and links to eight opinions.\n* {{cite news |work = [[The Atlantic]] |title = How Wikipedia Is Hostile to Women |date = 21 October 2015 |accessdate = 21 October 2015 |archivedate = 21 October 2015 |url = https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2015/10/how-wikipedia-is-hostile-to-women/411619/ |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151021174625/http://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2015/10/how-wikipedia-is-hostile-to-women/411619/ |first = Emma |last = Paling }}\n\n=== Research and advice ===\n* {{cite web |title = Wikipedia Survey: Overview Results |url = http://www.wikipediasurvey.org/docs/Wikipedia_Overview_15March2010-FINAL.pdf |last1 = Glott |first1 = Ruediger |last2 = Schmidt |first2 = Philipp |last3 = Ghosh |first3 = Rishab |date = March 2010 |website =  |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100414165445/http://wikipediasurvey.org/docs/Wikipedia_Overview_15March2010-FINAL.pdf |archivedate = 14 April 2010 |accessdate = 11 August 2014 }}\n*{{cite web |last1=Klein |first1=Maximilian |display-authors=etal. |title=Monitoring the Gender Gap with Wikidata Human Gender Indicators |url=http://wigi.wmflabs.org/monitoring-gender-gap.pdf|publisher=Cornell University Library |date=10 February 2015}}\n* {{Cite web |last = Tripp |first = Dawn Leonard |title = How to Edit Wikipedia: Lessons from a Female Contributor |work = Anita Borg Institute |accessdate = 6 February 2015 |url = http://anitaborg.org/news/blog/how-to-edit-wikipedia-lessons-from-a-female-contributor/ |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150209033907/http://anitaborg.org/news/blog/how-to-edit-wikipedia-lessons-from-a-female-contributor/ |archive-date = 9 February 2015 |url-status = dead }}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Hinnosaar|first1=Marit|title=Gender Inequality in New Media: Evidence from Wikipedia|journal = Journal of Economic Behavior & Organization |date = July 2019 |pages = 262\u2013276 |volume = 163 |doi = 10.1016/j.jebo.2019.04.020 |url=http://www.carloalberto.org/assets/working-papers/no.411.pdf}}\n*{{cite arXiv|last1=Vitulli|first1=Marie A.|title=Writing Women in Mathematics into Wikipedia |date=20 October 2017 |eprint=1710.11103v3 |class=math.HO}}\n*{{cite arxiv |last1=Wagner |first1=Claudia |last2=Garcia |first2=David |last3=Jadidi |first3=Mohsen |last4=Strohmaier |first4=Markus |year=2015 |title=It's a Man's Wikipedia? Assessing Gender Inequality in an Online Encyclopedia |eprint=1501.06307 |class=cs.CY}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Gender_gap Category:Gender gap] at Wikimedia Meta-Wiki\n* [https://www.academia.edu/41380442/Strangers_in_a_seemingly_open-to-all_website_the_gender_bias_in_Wikipedia Strangers in a seemingly open-to-all website. A research on the gender gap, by Dr. Shlomit Lir] \n{{Wikipedia |state=expanded}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Criticism of Wikipedia]]\n[[Category:Discrimination]]\n[[Category:Gender equality]]\n[[Category:Sexism]]\n", "name_user": "RAKMahoney", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor edit on language and spacing.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gender_bias_on_Wikipedia"}
{"title_page": "Hambirrao Mohite", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Hambirrao Mohite\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = c. May 01, 1630\n| birth_place   = Talbid, Maharashtra\n| death_date    = December 16, 1687(aged 57)\n| death_place   = Wai, Maharashtra\n| nickname      = \n| allegiance    = [[Maratha Empire]]\n| branch        = Maratha Army\n| serviceyears  = 1670-1687\n| rank          = Senapati(Military commander)\n| commands      = \n| spouse        = \n| battles       = \n| awards        = \n| relations     = Brother of Soyarabai ([[Shivaji]]'s spouse)\n| signature     = \n}}\n\n'''Hambirrao Mohite''' was the senapati (military commander) of [[Shivaji]]'s army. His sister [[Soyarabai|Soyarabai Mohite]] (second wife and maharani after the death of sai bai) was married to Shivaji. He also served the Kolhapur regency.\n\nAn able military general and fierce soldier, he executed several campaigns for Shivaji and later served under [[Sambhaji]]. He accompanied Shivaji to his famous Dakshin Digvijay (southern conquest) expedition.\n\nBorn as Hansaji Mohite, Shivaji conferred him the title \"Hambirrao\" and immediately declared Hambirrao as the next senapati in 1674 after [[Prataprao Gujar]]'s untimely death on the [[Nesari]] battlefield. He soon defeated the Mughal general Bahlol Khan and uplifted the lost morale of Maratha army. In 1677, Hambirrao led the Gadag seize and defeated the Adilshahi general Husein Khan of [[Koppal]].\n\nAfter the demise of Shivaji in 1680, Hambirrao backed his elder nephew Sambhaji (Shivaji's elder son) to claim the Maratha throne despite the demand of courtiers to crown [[Rajaram I|Rajaram]] (younger son of Shivaji). He also accompanied Sambhaji in his campaigns against the [[Mughal Empire|Mughals]]. \n[[File:Samadhi Hambirao.JPG|thumb|left|Gate to Samadhi of Hambirao Mohite]]\n\nHambirrao led the battle of [[Wai, Maharashtra|Wai]] on December 16, 1687 against the Mughals and defeated a relatively stronger Mughal army. He died after being hit by a cannonball. Hambirrao was succeeded by his 4 sons and a daughter, namely Santaji, Rangoji, Chandoji, Ranasing and [[Tarabai]]. Tarabai later married Shivaji's son Rajaram and became the Maratha queen.\n\nA memorial of Hambirrao Mohite is built at his hometown in [[Talbid]], [[Maharashtra]].\n\n{{commons category|Hambirrao Mohite}}\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Shivaji}}\n{{Maratha Empire}}\n\n[[Category:People of the Maratha Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Hambirrao Mohite\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = c. May 01, 1630\n| birth_place   = Talbid, Maharashtra\n| death_date    = December 16, 1687(aged 57)\n| death_place   = Wai, Maharashtra\n| nickname      = \n| allegiance    = [[Maratha Empire]]\n| branch        = Maratha Army\n| serviceyears  = 1670-1687\n| rank          = Senapati(Military commander)\n| commands      = \n| spouse        = \n| battles       = \n| awards        = \n| relations     = Brother of Soyarabai ([[Shivaji]]'s spouse)\n| signature     = \n}}\n\n'''Hambirrao Mohite''' was the senapati (military commander) of [[Shivaji]]'s army. His sister [[Soyarabai|Soyarabai Mohite]] (second wife and maharani after the death of sai bai) was married to Shivaji. He also served the Kolhapur regency.\n\nAn able military general and fierce soldier, he executed several campaigns for Shivaji and later served under [[Sambhaji]]. He accompanied Shivaji to his famous Dakshin Digvijay (southern conquest) expedition.\n\nBorn as Hansaji Mohite, Shivaji conferred him the title of \"Hambirrao\" and immediately declared Hambirrao as the next senapati in 1674 after [[Prataprao Gujar]]'s untimely death on the [[Nesari]] battlefield. He soon defeated the Mughal general Bahlol Khan and uplifted the lost morale of Maratha army. In 1677, Hambirrao led the Gadag seize and defeated the Adilshahi general Husein Khan of [[Koppal]].\n\nAfter the demise of Shivaji in 1680, Hambirrao backed his elder nephew Sambhaji (Shivaji's elder son) to claim the Maratha throne despite the demand of courtiers to crown [[Rajaram I|Rajaram]] (younger son of Shivaji). He also accompanied Sambhaji in his campaigns against the [[Mughal Empire|Mughals]]. \n[[File:Samadhi Hambirao.JPG|thumb|left|Gate to Samadhi of Hambirao Mohite]]\n\nHambirrao led the battle of [[Wai, Maharashtra|Wai]] on December 16, 1687 against the Mughals and defeated a relatively stronger Mughal army. He died after being hit by a cannonball. Hambirrao was succeeded by his 4 sons and a daughter, namely Santaji, Rangoji, Chandoji, Ranasing and [[Tarabai]]. Tarabai later married Shivaji's son Rajaram and became the Maratha queen.\n\nA memorial of Hambirrao Mohite is built at his hometown in [[Talbid]], [[Maharashtra]].\n\n{{commons category|Hambirrao Mohite}}\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Shivaji}}\n{{Maratha Empire}}\n\n[[Category:People of the Maratha Empire]]\n", "name_user": "Bramhesh Patil", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hambirrao_Mohite"}
{"title_page": "Immingham (Queens Road) electric railway station", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station\n|name        = Immingham (Queens Road)\n|locale      = [[Immingham]]\n|borough     = [[North East Lincolnshire]]\n|image_name  = \n|caption     = \n|original    = [[Great Central Railway]]\n|pregroup    = Great Central Railway\n|postgroup   = [[London and North Eastern Railway]]\n|platforms   = 0\n|coordinates = {{coord|53.6170|-0.1887|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n|gridref     = TA199149\n|years       = 1914\n|events      = extension electrified\n|years1      = 20 July 1915\n|events1     = passed Board of Trade inspection\n|years2      = 1939-45\n|events2     = overhead wires and points removed\n|years3      = by 1955\n|events3     = all trace removed{{sfn|Dow|1965|page=242}}{{sfn|Price|1991|page=76}}\n}}\n\n{{Grimsby & Immingham Electric Railway|collapse=yes}}\n{{Passenger Lines of North East Lincolnshire|collapse=yes}}\n'''Immingham (Queens Road) electric railway station''' would have been a halt on the [[Grimsby and Immingham Electric Railway]], but it never opened to fare paying passengers. Electrified track was laid to the station site and quarterly proving cars ran for nearly twentyfive years, but no revenue-earning car ever travelled to or from the halt.\n\n==Overview==\nThe electric railway was built primarily to carry workers between [[Grimsby]] and [[Immingham Dock]] which the [[Great Central Railway]] had built on a greenfield site in a sparsely populated area. The line was built by the Great Central and remained in railway ownership up to closure in 1961. It therefore appeared in railway timetables{{sfn|Bradshaw|1985|page=717}} and it was possible to buy through tickets between any of the stops on the line and anywhere on the national railway network,{{sfn|Price|1991|page=112}} though there never was any physical connection with any conventional track, nor with the tramways in Grimsby and Cleethorpes.\n\nIn modern parlance the vehicles would be described as trams, but they were typically referred to locally as \"tramcars\", with related things being called names such as \"tramcar halt\" and \"tramcar bridge\" with \"car\" a more common short form than \"tram.\"\n\n==Location and facilities==\n[[Immingham Town electric railway station|Immingham Town]] - known locally as \"Tramcar Halt\" - was situated outside the dock estate in what in 2012 was still open country. It was the nearest point to the line for its two lesser markets - railwaymen travelling to and from [[Immingham engine shed]] and residents of the village of Immingham,{{sfn|Price|1991|page=69}} by far the greatest market being dock workers. The station was nevertheless a third of a mile from the engine shed and a good mile from the village proper.\n\nWhen the line was proposed it included plans to continue from Immingham Town southwest along Queens Road to a point near the footpath to [[Immingham engine shed|engine shed]], or \"Loco\" as it was called locally. A 1966 aerial photograph shows a single decker bus in the near foreground very close to where the tramcar halt would have been.{{sfn|King|Hewins|1989|loc=Photo 43}}\n\nWhen the line was completed in 1913 the extension was omitted. Influential fingers were wagged so the [[Great Central Railway|company]] grudgingly built it to what would have been Queens Road Halt. The extension was single track with a passing loop at the halt.{{sfn|Price|1991|page=77}} Proving tramcars ran along the extension every quarter to maintain the right of way, but no revenue earning vehicle ever traversed it.{{sfn|Dow|1965|page=242}} The overhead wires and points were removed in the Second World War{{sfn|Price|1991|page=77}}{{sfn|WEA|1994|p=24}} and all trace of the unused branch had gone by 1955.\n\n==Services==\nUnusually among British tramways, services ran round the clock, particularly to provide for railway workers based at [[Immingham engine shed]], whose duties often involved starting or finishing at unsocial hours. Traffic was highly peaked, with convoys of tramcars leaving and arriving to match shift changes at the dock. It was normal for several tramcars to queue to reverse at Immingham Town at the peaks.\n\nHerein lay some of the reasons the Great Central never followed through with their stated intention of running cars to Queen Road, still less to Immingham Village beyond, as was implied in some earlier publicity{{sfn|Price|1991|page=74}} and repeatedly requested by Immingham Parish Council.{{sfn|Price|1991|page=76}} By a large margin the line's key market was dock workers, with railway staff a distant second and Immingham villagers a distant third. While these last would have paid fares, railway staff never did throughout the line's existence, so running tracks and services would be hopelessly uneconomic. Furthermore, travelling through to Queens Road or the village would have added significant time and potential disruption to the core users' journeys, with no benefit to them whatsoever.\n\n==Closure==\nThe line took some years to die, being cut back at the Grimsby end in 1956 then reduced to peak services only in 1959, when it disappeared from Bradshaw and through ticketing beyond the line was withdrawn.{{sfn|Bates|Bairstow|2005|page=85}} Formal closure of the line and Immingham Town tramcar halt came on Monday 3 July 1961, with the last tramcars running on Saturday 1 July 1961, when a convoy of six cars set off from Immingham Dock, nominally at 14:03.{{sfn|Skelsey|2011|page=239}} The last tramcar of this convoy and therefore the last from Immingham Town was Number 4.{{sfn|Price|1991|page=102}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe first track on the line to be removed was at Dock tramcar station, to give increased parking space. The process of demolition was piecemeal and even in 2013 many hints of the line remained, such as spun concrete masts near Immingham Town.\n\n<center>'''Former Services'''</center>\n{{Disused Rail Start}}\n{{Rail line\n|previous=\n|next=[[Immingham Town electric railway station|Immingham Town]]<br><small>Line built but never opened</small>\n|route=[[Great Central Railway]]<br><small>[[Grimsby and Immingham Electric Railway]]\n|col={{GCR colour}} }}\n{{end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Bates |first1=Chris |last2=Bairstow |first2=Martin |title=Railways in North Lincolnshire |year=2005 |publisher=Martin Bairstow |location=[[Leeds]] |isbn=978-1-871944-30-3 |ref=harv }}\n*{{Bradshaw-1922July}}\n*{{Dow-GC3}}\n*{{cite book |last1=King |first1=Paul K. |last2=Hewins |first2=Dave R. |title=Scenes from the Past: 5 The Railways around Grimsby, Cleethorpes, Immingham and North-east Lincolnshire |year=1989 |publisher=Foxline Publishing |location=[[Stockport]] |isbn=978-1-870119-04-7 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book| title = The Tramways of Grimsby, Immingham & Cleethorpes| first = J. H.|last= Price|publisher= Light Rail Transit Association|year=1991 |isbn=978-0-948106-10-1 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Skelsey |first1=Geoffrey |editor1-first=Michael |editor1-last=Blakemore |date= April 2011 |title= Flirting with the enemy, Railway Operated Electric Tramways in the United Kingdom |journal=Back Track |volume=25 |issue=4 |publisher=Atlantic Publishers |location=[[Easingwold]] |issn=0955-5382 | ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book| title=Immingham - the way we were : more memories of a marsh village |first1= |last1=[[Workers' Educational Association|WEA]] |publisher= [[Workers' Educational Association|WEA]]|location=[[Immingham]] |year=1994 |isbn=978-0-9524259-2-2 |ref=harv }}\n{{refend}}\n==Further material==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last=Anderson |first=Paul |title=Railways of Lincolnshire |year=1992 |publisher=Irwell Press |location=[[Oldham]] |isbn=978-1-871608-30-4 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book| title = The Tramways of South Yorkshire and Humberside |first1=W. H. |last1=Bett |first2=J. C. |last2=Gillham |publisher= Light Railway Transport League|location=[[London]] |year=1979 |isbn=978-0-900433-75-7 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite journal| title = Great Central Inter-Urban |first=T.|last= Feather|journal = Forward| publisher=Great Central Railway Society| issn= 0141-4488|date=February 1993}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Ludlam |first=A.J. |editor1-first=Rex |editor1-last=Kennedy |date=July 2006 |title=Immingham-Gateway to the Continent |journal=Steam Days |issue=203 |publisher=Redgauntlet Publications |location=[[Bournemouth]] |issn= 0269-0020 | ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book |last=Ludlam |first=A.J. |title=Railways to New Holland and the Humber Ferries, LP 198 |year=1996 |publisher=The Oakwood Press |location=[[Headington]] |isbn=978-0-85361-494-4 |ref=harv }}\n*{{citation| publisher = B&R Video Productions|volume=118 |medium=DVD | title= Electric Traction Archive}}, contains a fine archive section on the tramway\n*{{citation|publisher = Online Video, available via Great Central Railway Society |medium=DVD |title = The Passing of Pyewipe}}, solely about the tramways of Immingham, Grimsby & Cleethorpes\n{{refend}}\n==External links==\n*[http://maps.nls.uk/geo/explore/#zoom=15&lat=53.6263&lon=-0.1943&layers=6 Immingham as a green field site before the dock] ''National Library of Scotland''\n*[http://maps.nls.uk/geo/explore/#zoom=15&lat=53.6191&lon=-0.1792&layers=10 Immingham Town on an inter-War OS map] ''National Library of Scotland''\n*[http://maps.nls.uk/view/101587244 Immingham Queens Road tramcar halt on an OS map surveyed in 1930] ''National Library of Scotland''\n*[http://www.RailMapOnline.com/UKIEMap.php?lat=53.61687&lng=-0.18871 The station] ''Rail Map Online''\n*[http://www.lner.info/locos/Electric/immingham.shtml The Grimsby & Immingham Tramway] ''www.lner.info''\n*[http://www.davesrailpics.bravehost.com/pyewipe/tram.htm Tramway photos] ''davesrailpics''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20151211120033/http://lths.lutsociety.org.uk/library/PDF-160-1.pdf The Tramway] ''Local Transport History Soc''\n*[http://www.thornerailway.org.uk/page22.html Tramway remains] ''Thorne Railway''\n*[https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/2463058 Tramcar at Immingham Town] ''geograph''\n*[http://www.britainfromabove.org.uk/image/eaw029092?quicktabs_image=0#comment-864239 The site of the halt from the air] ''Britain from Above''\n\n{{Closed stations Lincolnshire}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Immingham Dock Electric Railway Station}}\n[[Category:Disused railway stations in the Borough of North East Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Former Great Central Railway stations]]\n[[Category:1915 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Immingham]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station\n|name        = Immingham (Queens Road)\n|locale      = [[Immingham]]\n|borough     = [[North East Lincolnshire]]\n|image_name  = \n|caption     = \n|original    = [[Great Central Railway]]\n|pregroup    = Great Central Railway\n|postgroup   = [[London and North Eastern Railway]]\n|platforms   = 0\n|coordinates = {{coord|53.6170|-0.1887|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n|gridref     = TA199149\n|years       = 1914\n|events      = extension electrified\n|years1      = 20 July 1915\n|events1     = passed Board of Trade inspection\n|years2      = 1939-45\n|events2     = overhead wires and points removed\n|years3      = by 1955\n|events3     = all trace removed{{sfn|Dow|1965|page=242}}{{sfn|Price|1991|page=76}}\n}}\n\n{{Grimsby & Immingham Electric Railway|collapse=yes}}\n{{Passenger Lines of North East Lincolnshire|collapse=yes}}\n'''Immingham (Queens Road) electric railway station''' would have been a halt on the [[Grimsby and Immingham Electric Railway]], but it never opened to fare paying passengers. Electrified track was laid to the station site and quarterly proving cars ran for nearly twentyfive years, but no revenue-earning car ever travelled to or from the halt.\n\n==Overview==\nThe electric railway was built primarily to carry workers between [[Grimsby]] and [[Immingham Dock]] which the [[Great Central Railway]] had built on a greenfield site in a sparsely populated area. The line was built by the Great Central and remained in railway ownership up to closure in 1961. It therefore appeared in railway timetables{{sfn|Bradshaw|1985|page=717}} and it was possible to buy through tickets between any of the stops on the line and anywhere on the national railway network,{{sfn|Price|1991|page=112}} though there never was any physical connection with any conventional track, nor with the tramways in Grimsby and Cleethorpes.\n\nIn modern parlance the vehicles would be described as trams, but they were typically referred to locally as \"tramcars\", with related things being called names such as \"tramcar halt\" and \"tramcar bridge\" with \"car\" a more common short form than \"tram.\"\n\n==Location and facilities==\n[[Immingham Town electric railway station|Immingham Town]] - known locally as \"Tramcar Halt\" - was situated outside the dock estate in what in 2012 was still open country. It was the nearest point to the line for its two lesser markets - railwaymen travelling to and from [[Immingham engine shed]] and residents of the village of Immingham,{{sfn|Price|1991|page=69}} by far the greatest market being dock workers. The station was nevertheless a third of a mile from the engine shed and a good mile from the village proper.\n\nWhen the line was proposed it included plans to continue from Immingham Town southwest along Queens Road to a point near the footpath to [[Immingham engine shed|engine shed]], or \"Loco\" as it was called locally. A 1966 aerial photograph shows a single decker bus in the near foreground very close to where the tramcar halt would have been.{{sfn|King|Hewins|1989|loc=Photo 43}}\n\nWhen the line was completed in 1913 the extension was omitted. Influential fingers were wagged so the [[Great Central Railway|company]] grudgingly built it to what would have been Queens Road Halt. The extension was single track with a passing loop at the halt.{{sfn|Price|1991|page=77}} Proving tramcars ran along the extension every quarter to maintain the right of way, but no revenue earning vehicle ever traversed it.{{sfn|Dow|1965|page=242}} The overhead wires and points were removed in the Second World War{{sfn|Price|1991|page=77}}{{sfn|WEA|1994|p=24}} and all trace of the unused branch had gone by 1955.\n\n==Services==\nUnusually among British tramways, services ran round the clock, particularly to provide for railway workers based at [[Immingham engine shed]], whose duties often involved starting or finishing at unsocial hours. Traffic was highly peaked, with convoys of tramcars leaving and arriving to match shift changes at the dock. It was normal for several tramcars to queue to reverse at Immingham Town at the peaks.\n\nHerein lay some of the reasons the Great Central never followed through with their stated intention of running cars to Queen Road, still less to Immingham Village beyond, as was implied in some earlier publicity{{sfn|Price|1991|page=74}} and repeatedly requested by Immingham Parish Council.{{sfn|Price|1991|page=76}} By a large margin the line's key market was dock workers, with railway staff a distant second and Immingham villagers a distant third. While these last would have paid fares, railway staff never did throughout the line's existence, so running tracks and services would be hopelessly uneconomic. Furthermore, travelling through to Queens Road or the village would have added significant time and potential disruption to the core users' journeys, with no benefit to them whatsoever.\n\n==Closure==\nThe line took some years to die, being cut back at the Grimsby end in 1956 then reduced to peak services only in 1959, when it disappeared from Bradshaw and through ticketing beyond the line was withdrawn.{{sfn|Bates|Bairstow|2005|page=85}} Formal closure of the line and Immingham Town tramcar halt came on Monday 3 July 1961, with the last tramcars running on Saturday 1 July 1961, when a convoy of six cars set off from Immingham Dock, nominally at 14:03.{{sfn|Skelsey|2011|page=239}} The last tramcar of this convoy and therefore the last from Immingham Town was Number 4.{{sfn|Price|1991|page=102}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe first track on the line to be removed was at Dock tramcar station, to give increased parking space. The process of demolition was piecemeal and even in 2013 many hints of the line remained, such as spun concrete masts near Immingham Town.\n\n<center>'''Former Services'''</center>\n{{Disused Rail Start}}\n{{Rail line\n|previous=\n|next=[[Immingham Town electric railway station|Immingham Town]]<br><small>Line built but never opened</small>\n|route=[[Great Central Railway]]<br><small>[[Grimsby and Immingham Electric Railway]]\n|col={{GCR colour}} }}\n{{end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Bates |first1=Chris |last2=Bairstow |first2=Martin |title=Railways in North Lincolnshire |year=2005 |publisher=Martin Bairstow |location=[[Leeds]] |isbn=978-1-871944-30-3 |ref=harv }}\n*{{Bradshaw-1922July}}\n*{{Dow-GC3}}\n*{{cite book |last1=King |first1=Paul K. |last2=Hewins |first2=Dave R. |title=Scenes from the Past: 5 The Railways around Grimsby, Cleethorpes, Immingham and North-east Lincolnshire |year=1989 |publisher=Foxline Publishing |location=[[Stockport]] |isbn=978-1-870119-04-7 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book| title = The Tramways of Grimsby, Immingham & Cleethorpes| first = J. H.|last= Price|publisher= Light Rail Transit Association|year=1991 |isbn=978-0-948106-10-1 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Skelsey |first1=Geoffrey |editor1-first=Michael |editor1-last=Blakemore |date= April 2011 |title= Flirting with the enemy, Railway Operated Electric Tramways in the United Kingdom |journal=Back Track |volume=25 |issue=4 |publisher=Atlantic Publishers |location=[[Easingwold]] |