sby & Cleethorpes\n{{refend}}\n==External links==\n*[http://maps.nls.uk/geo/explore/#zoom=15&lat=53.6263&lon=-0.1943&layers=6 Immingham as a green field site before the dock] ''National Library of Scotland''\n*[http://maps.nls.uk/geo/explore/#zoom=15&lat=53.6191&lon=-0.1792&layers=10 Immingham Town on an inter-War OS map] ''National Library of Scotland''\n*[http://maps.nls.uk/view/101587244 Immingham Queens Road tramcar halt on an OS map surveyed in 1930] ''National Library of Scotland''\n*[http://www.RailMapOnline.com/UKIEMap.php?lat=53.61687&lng=-0.18871 The station] ''Rail Map Online''\n*[http://www.lner.info/locos/Electric/immingham.shtml The Grimsby & Immingham Tramway] ''www.lner.info''\n*[http://www.davesrailpics.bravehost.com/pyewipe/tram.htm Tramway photos] ''davesrailpics''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20151211120033/http://lths.lutsociety.org.uk/library/PDF-160-1.pdf The Tramway] ''Local Transport History Soc''\n*[http://www.thornerailway.org.uk/page22.html Tramway remains] ''Thorne Railway''\n*[https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/2463058 Tramcar at Immingham Town] ''geograph''\n*[http://www.britainfromabove.org.uk/image/eaw029092?quicktabs_image=0#comment-864239 The site of the halt from the air] ''Britain from Above''\n\n{{Closed stations Lincolnshire}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Immingham Dock Electric Railway Station}}\n[[Category:Disused railway stations in the Borough of North East Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Former Great Central Railway stations]]\n[[Category:1915 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Immingham]]\n", "name_user": "Nempnet", "label": "safe", "comment": "removed duplicate further reading to fix  citation anchor", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Immingham_(Queens_Road)_electric_railway_station"}
{"title_page": "59th Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|{{more footnotes|date=August 2018}}{{refimprove|date=August 2018}}}}\n\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = 59th Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry\n| image = \n| caption = Flag of Massachusetts\n| dates = April 21, 1864 - August 9, 1865\n| allegiance = [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n| type = [[Infantry]]\n| battles = [[Battle of the Wilderness]]<br/>[[Battle of Spotsylvania Court House]]<br/>[[Cold Harbor]]<br/>[[First Battle of Petersburg]]<br/>[[Second Battle of Petersburg]]<br/>[[Siege of Petersburg]]<br/>[[Battle of the Crater]]<br/>[[Battle of Globe Tavern]]<br/>[[Battle of Peebles's Farm]]<br/>[[Battle of Boydton Plank Road]]<br/>[[Battle of Fort Stedman]]<br/>[[Appomattox Campaign]]<br/>[[Third Battle of Petersburg]]\n| commander1 = Jacob P. Gould\n| commander1_label = Commanders\n}}\n\nThe '''59th Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry''' was an [[infantry]] [[regiment]] that served in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n== Service ==\nOrganized at [[Readville, Boston|Reedville]] April 25, 1864. Moved to [[Alexandria, Virginia|Alexandria, Va]]., April 26-28. Attached to 1st Brigade, 2nd Division, [[IX Corps (Union Army)|IX Corps]], [[Army of the Potomac]], to September, 1864.<ref name=\"Dyer\">{{Cite book|title=A compendium of the War of the Rebellion|author=Dyer, Frederick H. |date=1959|publisher=T. Yoseloff|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|oclc=646869244}}</ref>\n\n== Detailed History ==\nThe 59th Regiment Mass. Vol. Inf. the Fourth Veteran Regiment, was organized at Readville, Mass., the first eight companies being mustered into the service between Jan. 14 and April 18, 1864.  The conditions of enlistment were the same as those in the other veteran regiments.  It participated in Army of the Potomac operations throughout its service. On 23 May 1865, it marched in the [[Grand Review of the Armies|Grand Review of the Army of the Potomac]]. The regiment was mustered out July 14, and on the following day took transportation for home.  Arriving at Readville, July 18, on the 26th its members were paid off and discharged.<ref name=\"MANG\">{{Cite book|title=Massachusetts soldiers, sailors, and marines in the civil war|author=Massachusetts. Adjutant General's Office|date=1937|oclc=870806724}}</ref>\n\n== Casualties ==\nThe regiment lost a total of 295 men during service; 10 officers and 129 enlisted men killed or mortally wounded and 156 enlisted men died of disease.<ref name=Losses\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/reglossescivilwar00foxwrich|title=Regimental losses in the American Civil War, 1861-1865. A treatise on the extent and nature of the mortuary losses in the Union regiments, with full and exhaustive statistics compiled from the official records on file in the state military bureaus and at Washington|last=Fox|first=William|publisher=Albany Pub. Co|year=1889|isbn=|location=Albany, NY|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n<references />\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|author=Dyer, Frederick H. |title=A Compendium of the War of the Rebellion|url=https://www.amazon.com/Compendium-War-Rebellion-Frederick-Dyer/dp/B01BUFJ76Q|publisher=Dyer Pub. Co.|location=Des Moines, IA|year=1908|asin=B01BUFJ76Q}}{{PD-notice}}\n*{{cite book |title=Massachusetts in the War, 1861&ndash;1865 |last=Bowen |first=James L. |authorlink= |year=1889 |place=Springfield, Massachusetts |publisher=Clark W. Bryan & Co |oclc=1986476 |url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_K0tLhkfW1wwC}}{{PD-notice}}\n*{{cite book |title=A History of Massachusetts in the Civil War |last=Schouler |first=William |authorlink=William Schouler |year=1868 |origyear= |place=Boston |publisher=E.P. Dutton & Co |oclc=2662693 |url=https://archive.org/details/ahistorymassach01schogoog}}{{PD-notice}}\n* {{cite book|author=Stevens, Jesse F, The Adjutant General|title=Massachusetts Soldiers, Sailors, and Marines in the Civil War,|url=https://archive.org/details/massachusettssol11931mass/mode/2up|publisher=Norwood Press|location=Norwood, MA|date=1931|ASIN=B000UH94DC}}.{{PD-notice}}\n* U.S. War Department, [http://cdl.library.cornell.edu/moa/browse.monographs/waro.html ''The War of the Rebellion'']: ''a Compilation of the [[Official Records of the American Civil War|Official Records]] of the Union and Confederate Armies''. Washington, DC: U.S. Government Printing Office, 1880&ndash;1901.{{PD-notice}}\n== External Links ==\n\n* http://www.fortwiki.com/Fort_Meikie\n* http://www.fortwiki.com/Fort_Mahone\n* https://www.nps.gov/frsp/learn/photosmultimedia/germanna.htm\n\n[[Category:Massachusetts Civil War regiments]]\n[[Category:1861 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1864]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1865]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|{{more footnotes|date=August 2018}}{{refimprove|date=August 2018}}}}\n\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = 59th Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry\n| image = \n| caption = Flag of Massachusetts\n| dates = April 21, 1864 - August 9, 1865\n| allegiance = [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n| type = [[Infantry]]\n| battles = [[Battle of the Wilderness]]<br/>[[Battle of Spotsylvania Court House]]<br/>[[Cold Harbor]]<br/>[[First Battle of Petersburg]]<br/>[[Second Battle of Petersburg]]<br/>[[Siege of Petersburg]]<br/>[[Battle of the Crater]]<br/>[[Battle of Globe Tavern]]<br/>[[Battle of Peebles's Farm]]<br/>[[Battle of Boydton Plank Road]]<br/>[[Battle of Fort Stedman]]<br/>[[Appomattox Campaign]]<br/>[[Third Battle of Petersburg]]\n| commander1 = Jacob P. Gould\n| commander1_label = Commanders\n}}\n\nThe '''59th Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry''' was an [[infantry]] [[regiment]] that served in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n== Service ==\nOrganized at [[Readville, Boston|Reedville]] April 25, 1864. Moved to [[Alexandria, Virginia|Alexandria, Va]]., April 26-28. Attached to 1st Brigade, 2nd Division, [[IX Corps (Union Army)|IX Corps]], [[Army of the Potomac]], to September, 1864.<ref name=\"Dyer\">{{Cite book|title=A compendium of the War of the Rebellion|author=Dyer, Frederick H. |date=1959|publisher=T. Yoseloff|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|oclc=646869244}}</ref>\n\n== Detailed History ==\nThe 59th Regiment Mass. Vol. Inf. the Fourth Veteran Regiment, was organized at Readville, Mass., the first eight companies being mustered into the service between Jan. 14 and April 18, 1864.  The conditions of enlistment were the same as those in the other veteran regiments.  It participated in Army of the Potomac operations throughout its service. On 23 May 1865, it marched in the [[Grand Review of the Armies|Grand Review of the Army of the Potomac]]. The regiment was mustered out July 14, and on the following day took transportation for home.  Arriving at Readville, July 18, on the 26th its members were paid off and discharged.<ref name=\"MANG\">{{Cite book|title=Massachusetts soldiers, sailors, and marines in the civil war|author=Massachusetts. Adjutant General's Office|date=1937|oclc=870806724}}</ref>\n\n== Casualties ==\nThe regiment lost a total of 295 men during service; 10 officers and 129 enlisted men killed or mortally wounded and 156 enlisted men died of disease.<ref name=Losses\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/reglossescivilwar00foxwrich|title=Regimental losses in the American Civil War, 1861-1865. A treatise on the extent and nature of the mortuary losses in the Union regiments, with full and exhaustive statistics compiled from the official records on file in the state military bureaus and at Washington|last=Fox|first=William|publisher=Albany Pub. Co|year=1889|isbn=|location=Albany, NY|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Massachusetts Civil War units]]\n\n== Notes ==\n<references />\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|author=Dyer, Frederick H. |title=A Compendium of the War of the Rebellion|url=https://www.amazon.com/Compendium-War-Rebellion-Frederick-Dyer/dp/B01BUFJ76Q|publisher=Dyer Pub. Co.|location=Des Moines, IA|year=1908|asin=B01BUFJ76Q}}{{PD-notice}}\n*{{cite book |title=Massachusetts in the War, 1861&ndash;1865 |last=Bowen |first=James L. |authorlink= |year=1889 |place=Springfield, Massachusetts |publisher=Clark W. Bryan & Co |oclc=1986476 |url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_K0tLhkfW1wwC}}{{PD-notice}}\n*{{cite book |title=A History of Massachusetts in the Civil War |last=Schouler |first=William |authorlink=William Schouler |year=1868 |origyear= |place=Boston |publisher=E.P. Dutton & Co |oclc=2662693 |url=https://archive.org/details/ahistorymassach01schogoog}}{{PD-notice}}\n* {{cite book|author=Stevens, Jesse F, The Adjutant General|title=Massachusetts Soldiers, Sailors, and Marines in the Civil War,|url=https://archive.org/details/massachusettssol11931mass/mode/2up|publisher=Norwood Press|location=Norwood, MA|date=1931|ASIN=B000UH94DC}}.{{PD-notice}}\n* U.S. War Department, [http://cdl.library.cornell.edu/moa/browse.monographs/waro.html ''The War of the Rebellion'']: ''a Compilation of the [[Official Records of the American Civil War|Official Records]] of the Union and Confederate Armies''. Washington, DC: U.S. Government Printing Office, 1880&ndash;1901.{{PD-notice}}\n== External Links ==\n\n* http://www.fortwiki.com/Fort_Meikie\n* http://www.fortwiki.com/Fort_Mahone\n* https://www.nps.gov/frsp/learn/photosmultimedia/germanna.htm\n\n[[Category:Massachusetts Civil War regiments]]\n[[Category:1861 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1864]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1865]]\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/59th_Regiment_Massachusetts_Volunteer_Infantry"}
